# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: standard-model
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] In particle physics, the **electroweak interaction** or **electroweak force** is the unified description of two of the fundamental interactions of nature: electromagnetism (electromagnetic interaction), and the weak interaction.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] Although these two forces appear very different at everyday low energies, the theory models them as two different aspects of the same force.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] Above the unification energy, on the order of 246 GeV, they would merge into a single force.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] Thus, if the temperature is high enough – approximately 1015 K – then the electromagnetic force and weak force merge into a combined electroweak force.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] During the quark epoch (shortly after the Big Bang), the electroweak force split into the electromagnetic and weak force.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] It is thought that the required temperature of 1015 K has not been seen widely throughout the universe since before the quark epoch, and currently the highest human-made temperature in thermal equilibrium is around 5.5×1012 K (from the Large Hadron Collider).
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] Sheldon Glashow, Abdus Salam, and Steven Weinberg were awarded the 1979 Nobel Prize in Physics for their contributions to the unification of the weak and electromagnetic interaction between elementary particles, known as the **Weinberg–Salam theory**.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] In 1999, Gerardus 't Hooft and Martinus Veltman were awarded the Nobel prize for showing that the electroweak theory is renormalizable.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] After the Wu experiment in 1956 discovered parity violation in the weak interaction, a search began for a way to relate the weak and electromagnetic interactions.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] Extending his doctoral advisor Julian Schwinger's work, Sheldon Glashow first experimented with introducing two different symmetries, one chiral and one achiral, and combined them such that their overall symmetry was unbroken.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] This did not yield a renormalizable theory, and its gauge symmetry had to be broken by hand as no spontaneous mechanism was known, but it predicted a new particle, the Z boson.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] This received little notice, as it matched no experimental finding.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] In 1964, Salam and John Clive Ward had the same idea, but predicted a massless photon and three massive gauge bosons with a manually broken symmetry.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] Later around 1967, while investigating spontaneous symmetry breaking, Weinberg found a set of symmetries predicting a massless, neutral gauge boson.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] Initially rejecting such a particle as useless, he later realized his symmetries produced the electroweak force, and he proceeded to predict rough masses for the W and Z bosons.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] Significantly, he suggested this new theory was renormalizable.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] In 1971, Gerard 't Hooft proved that spontaneously broken gauge symmetries are renormalizable even with massive gauge bosons.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] Mathematically, electromagnetism is unified with the weak interactions as a Yang–Mills field with an SU(2) × U(1) gauge group, which describes the formal operations that can be applied to the electroweak gauge fields without changing the dynamics of the system.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] These fields are the weak isospin fields W1, W2, and W3, and the weak hypercharge field B.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] This invariance is known as **electroweak symmetry**.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] The generators of SU(2) and U(1) are given the name weak isospin (labeled T) and weak hypercharge (labeled Y) respectively.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] These then give rise to the gauge bosons that mediate the electroweak interactions – the three W bosons of weak isospin (*W*1, *W*2, and *W*3), and the *B* boson of weak hypercharge, respectively, all of which are "initially" massless.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] These are not physical fields yet, before spontaneous symmetry breaking and the associated Higgs mechanism.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] The electric charge arises as the particular linear combination (nontrivial) of Yw (weak hypercharge) and the T3 component of weak isospin ( $Q=T_{3}+{\tfrac {1}{2}}\,Y_{\mathrm {W} }$ ) that does *not* couple to the Higgs boson.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] That is to say: the Higgs and the electromagnetic field have no effect on each other, at the level of the fundamental forces ("tree level"), while any *other* combination of the hypercharge and the weak isospin must interact with the Higgs.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] This causes an apparent separation between the weak force, which interacts with the Higgs, and electromagnetism, which does not.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] Mathematically, the electric charge is a specific combination of the hypercharge and T3 outlined in the figure.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] U(1)em (the symmetry group of electromagnetism only) is defined to be the group generated by this special linear combination, and the symmetry described by the U(1)em group is unbroken, since it does not *directly* interact with the Higgs.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] The axes representing the particles have essentially just been rotated, in the (W3, B) plane, by the angle θw.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] where $W_{a}^{\mu \nu }$ ( $a=1,2,3$ ) and $B^{\mu \nu }$ are the field strength tensors for the weak isospin and weak hypercharge gauge fields.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] ${\mathcal {L}}_{f}$ is the kinetic term for the Standard Model fermions.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] where the subscript j sums over the three generations of fermions; Q, u, and d are the left-handed doublet, right-handed singlet up, and right handed singlet down quark fields; and L and e are the left-handed doublet and right-handed singlet electron fields.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] Here $\ Y\$ is the weak hypercharge and the $\ T_{j}\$ are the components of the weak isospin.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] where v is the vacuum expectation value.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] and generates their masses, manifest when the Higgs field acquires a nonzero vacuum expectation value, discussed next.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] The Lagrangian reorganizes itself as the Higgs field acquires a non-vanishing vacuum expectation value dictated by the potential of the previous section.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] As a result of this rewriting, the symmetry breaking becomes manifest.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] In the history of the universe, this is believed to have happened shortly after the hot big bang, when the universe was at a temperature 159.5±1.5 GeV (assuming the Standard Model of particle physics).
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] Due to its complexity, this Lagrangian is best described by breaking it up into several parts as follows.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] with X to be replaced by the relevant field ( $A,$ $Z,$ $W^{\pm }$ ) and f abc by the structure constants of the appropriate gauge group.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] where $\ q_{f}\$ is the fermions' electric charges.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] where $T_{f}^{3}$ is the fermions' weak isospin.
[src:standard-model/electroweak-interaction] where $\ \nu \$ is the right-handed singlet neutrino field, and the CKM matrix $M_{ij}^{\mathrm {CKM} }$ determines the mixing between mass and weak eigenstates of the quarks.
[src:standard-model/gluon] A **gluon** (/ˈɡluːɒn/ *GLOO-on*) is a type of massless elementary particle that mediates the strong interaction between quarks, acting as the exchange particle for the interaction.
[src:standard-model/gluon] Gluons are massless vector bosons, thereby having a spin of 1.
[src:standard-model/gluon] Through the strong interaction, gluons bind quarks into groups according to quantum chromodynamics (QCD), forming hadrons such as protons and neutrons.
[src:standard-model/gluon] Gluons carry the color charge of the strong interaction, thereby participating in the strong interaction as well as mediating it.
[src:standard-model/gluon] Because gluons carry the color charge, QCD is more difficult to analyze compared to quantum electrodynamics (QED) where the photon carries no electric charge.
[src:standard-model/gluon] The term was coined by Murray Gell-Mann in 1962 for being similar to an adhesive or glue that keeps the nucleus together.
[src:standard-model/gluon] Together with the quarks, these particles were referred to as partons by Richard Feynman.
[src:standard-model/gluon] The gluon is a vector boson, which means it has a spin of 1 *ħ*.
[src:standard-model/gluon] While massive spin-1 particles have three polarization states, massless gauge bosons like the gluon have only two polarization states because gauge invariance requires the field polarization to be transverse to the direction that the gluon is traveling.
[src:standard-model/gluon] In quantum field theory, unbroken gauge invariance requires that gauge bosons have zero mass.
[src:standard-model/gluon] Experiments limit the gluon's rest mass (if any) to less than a few MeV/*c*2.
[src:standard-model/gluon] The gluon has negative intrinsic parity.
[src:standard-model/gluon] There are eight independent types of gluons in QCD.
[src:standard-model/gluon] This is unlike the photon of QED or the three W and Z bosons of the weak interaction.
[src:standard-model/gluon] Additionally, gluons are subject to the color charge phenomena.
[src:standard-model/gluon] Quarks carry three types of color charge; antiquarks carry three types of anticolor.
[src:standard-model/gluon] This gives nine *possible* combinations of color and anticolor in gluons.
[src:standard-model/gluon] These *possible* combinations are only *effective* states, not the *actual* observed color states of gluons.
[src:standard-model/gluon] To understand how they are combined, it is necessary to consider the mathematics of color charge in more detail.
[src:standard-model/gluon] The stable strongly interacting particles, including hadrons like the proton or the neutron, are observed to be "colorless".
[src:standard-model/gluon] More precisely, they are in a "color singlet" state, and mathematically analogous to a *spin* singlet state.
[src:standard-model/gluon] The states allow interaction with other color singlets, but not other color states; because long-range gluon interactions do not exist, this illustrates that gluons in the singlet state do not exist either.
[src:standard-model/gluon] If one could measure the color of the state, there would be equal probabilities of it being red–antired, blue–antiblue, or green–antigreen.
[src:standard-model/gluon] There are eight remaining independent color states corresponding to the "eight types" or "eight colors" of gluons.
[src:standard-model/gluon] Since the states can be mixed together, there are multiple ways of presenting these states.
[src:standard-model/gluon] These are equivalent to the Gell-Mann matrices.
[src:standard-model/gluon] The critical feature of these particular eight states is that they are linearly independent, and also independent of the singlet state, hence 32 − 1 or 23.
[src:standard-model/gluon] There is no way to add any combination of these states to produce any others.
[src:standard-model/gluon] It is also impossible to add them to make *r**r*, *g**g*, or *b**b* the forbidden singlet state.
[src:standard-model/gluon] There are many other possible choices, but all are mathematically equivalent, at least equally complicated, and give the same physical results.
[src:standard-model/gluon] Formally, QCD is a gauge theory with SU(3) gauge symmetry.
[src:standard-model/gluon] Quarks are introduced as spinors in *N*f flavors, each in the fundamental representation (triplet, denoted **3**) of the color gauge group, SU(3).
[src:standard-model/gluon] The gluons are vectors in the adjoint representation (octets, denoted **8**) of color SU(3).
[src:standard-model/gluon] For a general gauge group, the number of force-carriers, like photons or gluons, is always equal to the dimension of the adjoint representation.
[src:standard-model/gluon] For the simple case of SU(*n*), the dimension of this representation is *n*2 − 1.
[src:standard-model/gluon] In group theory, there are no color singlet gluons because quantum chromodynamics has an SU(3) rather than a U(3) symmetry.
[src:standard-model/gluon] There is no known *a priori* reason for one group to be preferred over the other, but as discussed above, the experimental evidence supports SU(3).
[src:standard-model/gluon] If the group were U(3), the ninth (colorless singlet) gluon would behave like a "second photon" and not like the other eight gluons.
[src:standard-model/gluon] Since gluons themselves carry color charge, they participate in strong interactions.
[src:standard-model/gluon] These gluon–gluon interactions constrain color fields to string-like objects called "flux tubes", which exert constant force when stretched.
[src:standard-model/gluon] Due to this force, quarks are confined within composite particles called hadrons.
[src:standard-model/gluon] This effectively limits the range of the strong interaction to 10−15 m, roughly the size of a nucleon.
[src:standard-model/gluon] Beyond a certain distance, the energy of the flux tube binding two quarks increases linearly.
[src:standard-model/gluon] At a large enough distance, it becomes energetically more favorable to pull a quark–antiquark pair out of the vacuum rather than increase the length of the flux tube.
[src:standard-model/gluon] One consequence of the hadron-confinement property of gluons is that they are not directly involved in the nuclear forces between hadrons.
[src:standard-model/gluon] The force mediators for these are other hadrons called mesons.
[src:standard-model/gluon] Although in the normal phase of QCD single gluons may not travel freely, it is predicted that there exist hadrons that are formed entirely of gluons — called glueballs.
[src:standard-model/gluon] There are also conjectures about other exotic hadrons in which real gluons (as opposed to virtual ones found in ordinary hadrons) would be primary constituents.
[src:standard-model/gluon] Beyond the normal phase of QCD (at extreme temperatures and pressures), quark–gluon plasma forms.
[src:standard-model/gluon] In such a plasma there are no hadrons; quarks and gluons become free particles.
[src:standard-model/gluon] Quarks and gluons (colored) manifest themselves by fragmenting into more quarks and gluons, which in turn hadronize into normal (colorless) particles, correlated in jets.
[src:standard-model/gluon] As revealed in 1978 summer conferences, the PLUTO detector at the electron-positron collider DORIS (DESY) produced the first evidence that the hadronic decays of the very narrow resonance Υ(9.46) could be interpreted as three-jet event topologies produced by three gluons.
[src:standard-model/gluon] Later, published analyses by the same experiment confirmed this interpretation and also the spin = 1 nature of the gluon (see also the recollection and PLUTO experiments).
[src:standard-model/gluon] In summer 1979, at higher energies at the electron-positron collider PETRA (DESY), again three-jet topologies were observed, now clearly visible and interpreted as qq gluon bremsstrahlung, by TASSO, MARK-J and PLUTO experiments (later in 1980 also by JADE).
[src:standard-model/gluon] The spin = 1 property of the gluon was confirmed in 1980 by TASSO and PLUTO experiments (see also the review).
[src:standard-model/gluon] In 1991 a subsequent experiment at the LEP storage ring at CERN again confirmed this result.
[src:standard-model/gluon] The gluons play an important role in the elementary strong interactions between quarks and gluons, described by QCD and studied particularly at the electron-proton collider HERA at DESY.
[src:standard-model/gluon] The number and momentum distribution of the gluons in the proton (gluon density) have been measured by two experiments, H1 and ZEUS, in the years 1996–2007.
[src:standard-model/gluon] The gluon contribution to the proton spin has been studied by the HERMES experiment at HERA.
[src:standard-model/gluon] The gluon density in the photon (when behaving hadronically) also has been measured.
[src:standard-model/gluon] Color confinement is verified by the failure of free quark searches (searches of fractional charges).
[src:standard-model/gluon] Quarks are normally produced in pairs (quark + antiquark) to compensate the quantum color and flavor numbers; however at Fermilab single production of top quarks has been shown.
[src:standard-model/gluon] Deconfinement was claimed in 2000 at CERN SPS in heavy-ion collisions, and it implies a new state of matter: quark–gluon plasma, less interactive than in the nucleus, almost as in a liquid.
[src:standard-model/gluon] It was found at the Relativistic Heavy Ion Collider (RHIC) at Brookhaven in the years 2004–2010 by four contemporaneous experiments.
[src:standard-model/gluon] A quark–gluon plasma state has been confirmed at the CERN Large Hadron Collider (LHC) by the three experiments ALICE, ATLAS and CMS in 2010.
[src:standard-model/gluon] Jefferson Lab's Continuous Electron Beam Accelerator Facility, in Newport News, Virginia, is one of 10 Department of Energy facilities doing research on gluons.
[src:standard-model/gluon] The Virginia lab was competing with another facility – Brookhaven National Laboratory, on Long Island, New York – for funds to build a new electron-ion collider.
[src:standard-model/gluon] In December 2019, the US Department of Energy selected the Brookhaven National Laboratory to host the electron-ion collider.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] The **Higgs boson**, sometimes called the **Higgs particle**, is an elementary particle in the Standard Model of particle physics produced by the quantum excitation of the Higgs field, one of the fields in particle physics theory.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] In the Standard Model, the Higgs particle is a massive scalar boson that couples to (interacts with) particles whose mass arises from their interactions with the Higgs field, has zero spin, even (positive) parity, no electric charge, and no color charge.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] It is also very unstable, decaying into other particles almost immediately upon generation.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] The Higgs field is a scalar field with two neutral and two electrically charged components that form a complex doublet of the weak isospin SU(2) symmetry.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] The existence of the Higgs field became the last unverified part of the Standard Model of particle physics, and for several decades was considered "the central problem in particle physics".
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] Both the field and the boson are named after physicist Peter Higgs, who in 1964, along with five other scientists in three teams, proposed the Higgs mechanism, a way for some particles to acquire mass.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] All fundamental particles known at the time should be massless at very high energies, but fully explaining how some particles gain mass at lower energies had been extremely difficult.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] If these ideas were correct, a particle known as a scalar boson (with certain properties) should also exist.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] This particle was called the Higgs boson and could be used to test whether the Higgs field was the correct explanation.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] After a 40-year search, a subatomic particle with the expected properties was discovered in 2012 by the ATLAS and CMS experiments at the Large Hadron Collider (LHC) at CERN near Geneva, Switzerland.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] The new particle was subsequently confirmed to match the expected properties of a Higgs boson.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] Physicists from two of the three teams, Peter Higgs and François Englert, were awarded the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2013 for their theoretical predictions.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] Although Higgs's name has come to be associated with this theory, several researchers between about 1960 and 1972 independently developed different parts of it.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] In the media, the Higgs boson has often been called the "**God particle**" after the 1993 book *The God Particle* by Nobel Laureate Leon M.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] The name has been criticised by physicists, including Peter Higgs.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] Physicists explain the fundamental particles and forces of the universe in terms of the Standard Model – a widely accepted framework based on quantum field theory that predicts almost all known particles and forces aside from gravity with great accuracy.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] (A separate theory, general relativity, is used for gravity.) In the Standard Model, the particles and forces in nature (aside from gravity) arise from properties of quantum fields known as gauge invariance and symmetries.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] Forces in the Standard Model are transmitted by particles known as gauge bosons.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] Gauge-invariant theories are theories with a useful feature, namely that changes to certain quantities make no difference to experimental outcomes.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] For example, increasing the electric potential of an electromagnet by 100 volts does not itself cause any change to the magnetic field that it produces.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] Similarly, the measured speed of light in vacuum remains unchanged, whatever the location in time and space, and whatever the local gravitational field.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] In these theories, the gauge is a quantity that can be changed with no resultant effect.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] This independence of the results from some changes is called gauge invariance, and these changes reflect symmetries of the underlying physics.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] These symmetries provide constraints on the fundamental forces and particles of the physical world.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] Gauge invariance is therefore an important property within particle physics theory.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] The gauge symmetries are closely connected to conservation laws and are described mathematically using group theory.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] Quantum field theory and the Standard Model are both gauge-invariant theories – meaning that the gauge symmetries allow theoretical derivation of properties of the universe.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] As a result of these failures, gauge theories began to fall into disrepute.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] The problem was that symmetry requirements for these two forces incorrectly predicted that the weak force's gauge bosons (W and Z) would have zero mass (in the specialized terminology of particle physics, "mass" refers specifically to a particle's rest mass).
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] But experiments showed the W and Z gauge bosons had non-zero (rest) mass.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] Further, many promising solutions seemed to require the existence of extra particles known as Goldstone bosons, but evidence suggested these did not exist.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] This meant that either gauge invariance was an incorrect approach, or something unknown was giving the weak force's W and Z bosons their mass, and doing it in a way that did not imply the existence of Goldstone bosons.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] By the late 1950s and early 1960s, physicists were at a loss as to how to resolve these issues, or how to create a comprehensive theory for particle physics.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] In the late 1950s, Yoichiro Nambu recognised that spontaneous symmetry breaking, a process whereby a symmetric system becomes asymmetric, could occur under certain conditions.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] Symmetry breaking is when some variable takes on a value that does not reflect the symmetries that the underlying laws have, such as when the space of all stable configurations possesses a given symmetry but the stable configurations do not individually possess that symmetry.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] In 1962, physicist Philip Anderson, an expert in condensed matter physics, observed that symmetry breaking plays a role in superconductivity, and suggested that it could also be part of the answer to the problem of gauge invariance in particle physics.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] Specifically, Anderson suggested that the Goldstone bosons that would result from symmetry breaking might instead, in some circumstances, be "absorbed" by the massless W and Z bosons.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] If so, perhaps the Goldstone bosons would not exist, and the W and Z bosons could gain mass, solving both problems at once.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] Similar behaviour was already theorised in superconductivity.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] In 1964, this was shown to be theoretically possible by physicists Abraham Klein and Benjamin Lee, at least for some limited (non-relativistic) cases.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] Following the 1963 and early 1964 papers, three groups of researchers independently developed these theories more completely, in what became known as the 1964 PRL symmetry breaking papers.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] All three groups reached similar conclusions and for all cases, not just some limited cases.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] They showed that the conditions for electroweak symmetry would be "broken" if an unusual type of field existed throughout the universe, and indeed, there would be no Goldstone bosons and some existing bosons would acquire mass.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] The field required for this to happen (which was purely hypothetical at the time) became known as the *Higgs field* (after Peter Higgs, one of the researchers) and the mechanism by which it led to symmetry breaking became known as the *Higgs mechanism*.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] A key feature of the necessary field is that the field would have *less* energy when it had a non-zero value than when it was zero, unlike every other known field; therefore, the Higgs field has a non-zero value (or *vacuum expectation*) everywhere.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] This non-zero value could in theory break electroweak symmetry.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] It was the first proposal that was able to show, within a gauge invariant theory, how the weak force gauge bosons could have mass despite their governing symmetry.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] During the 1970s, these theories rapidly became the Standard Model of particle physics.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] To allow symmetry breaking, the Standard Model includes a field of the kind needed to "break" electroweak symmetry and give particles their correct mass.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] This field, which became known as the Higgs field, was hypothesized to exist throughout space, and to break some symmetry laws of the electroweak interaction, triggering the Higgs mechanism.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] It would therefore cause the W and Z gauge bosons of the weak force to be massive at all temperatures below an extremely high value.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] When the weak force bosons acquire mass, this affects the distance they can freely travel, which becomes very small, also matching experimental findings.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] Furthermore, it was later realised that the same field would also explain, in a different way, why other fundamental constituents of matter (including electrons and quarks) have mass.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] Unlike all other known fields, such as the electromagnetic field, the Higgs field is a scalar field, and has a non-zero average value in vacuum.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] Prior to the discovery of the Higgs Boson, there was no direct evidence that the Higgs field exists, but even without direct evidence, the accuracy of predictions within the Standard Model led scientists to believe the theory might be correct.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] By the 1980s, the question of whether the Higgs field exists, and whether the entire Standard Model is correct, had come to be regarded as one of the most important unanswered questions in particle physics.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] For many decades, scientists had no way to determine whether the Higgs field exists because the technology needed for its detection did not exist at that time.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] If the Higgs field did exist, then it would be unlike any other known fundamental field, but it also was possible that these key ideas, or even the entire Standard Model, were somehow incorrect.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] The hypothesised Higgs theory made several key predictions.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] One crucial prediction was that a matching particle, called the Higgs boson, should also exist.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] Proving the existence of the Higgs boson would prove the existence of the Higgs field, and therefore finally prove the Standard Model.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] Therefore, there was an extensive search for the Higgs boson as a way to prove the Higgs field itself exists.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] Although the Higgs field would exist and be nonzero everywhere, proving its existence was far from easy.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] In principle, it can be proved to exist by detecting its excitations, which manifest as Higgs particles (Higgs bosons), but these are extremely difficult to produce and detect due to the energy required to produce them and their very rare production even if there is sufficient energy available.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] It was, therefore, several decades before the first evidence of the Higgs boson would be found.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] Particle colliders, detectors, and computers capable of looking for Higgs bosons took more than 30 years (c.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] The importance of this fundamental question led to a 40-year search, and the construction of one of the world's most expensive and complex experimental facility to date, CERN's Large Hadron Collider (LHC), in an attempt to create Higgs bosons and other particles for observation and study.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] On 4 July 2012, the discovery of a new particle with a mass between 125 and 127 GeV/*c*2 was announced; physicists suspected that it was the Higgs boson.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] Since then, the particle has been shown to behave, interact, and decay in many of the ways predicted for Higgs particles by the Standard Model, including having even parity and zero spin, two fundamental attributes of a Higgs boson.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] This also means it is the first elementary scalar particle discovered in nature.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] By March 2013, the existence of the Higgs boson was confirmed, and therefore the concept of some type of Higgs field throughout space is strongly supported.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] The presence of the field, confirmed by experiment, explains why some fundamental particles have (a rest) mass, despite the symmetries controlling their interactions implying that they should be "massless".
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] It also resolves several other long-standing problems, such as the reason for the extremely short distance travelled by the weak force bosons, and therefore the weak force's extremely short range.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] As of 2018, in-depth research shows the particle continuing to behave in line with predictions for the Standard Model's Higgs boson.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] More studies are needed to verify with higher precision that the discovered particle has all of the properties predicted or whether, as described by some theories, multiple Higgs bosons exist.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] The nature and properties of this field are being investigated further, using more data collected at the LHC.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] Various analogies have been used to describe the Higgs field and boson, including analogies with well-known symmetry-breaking effects such as the rainbow and prism, electric fields, and ripples on the surface of water.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] In the Standard Model, the **Higgs** **boson** is a massive scalar boson whose mass must be found experimentally.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] It is the only particle that remains massive even at very high energies.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] It has zero spin, even (positive) parity, no electric charge, no colour charge, and it couples to (interacts with) mass.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] It is also very unstable, decaying into other particles almost immediately via several possible pathways.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] The **Higgs field** is a scalar field, with two neutral and two electrically charged components that form a complex doublet of the weak isospin SU(2) symmetry.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] Unlike any other known quantum field, it has a sombrero potential.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] This shape means that below extremely high cross-over temperature of 159.5±1.5 GeV/*k*B such as those seen during the first picosecond (10−12 s) of the Big Bang, the Higgs field in its ground state has less energy when it is nonzero, resulting in a nonzero vacuum expectation value.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] Therefore, in today's universe the Higgs field has a nonzero value everywhere (including in otherwise empty space).
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] This nonzero value in turn breaks the weak isospin SU(2) symmetry of the electroweak interaction everywhere.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] The remaining electrically neutral component either manifests as a Higgs boson, or may couple separately to other particles known as fermions (via Yukawa couplings), causing these to acquire mass as well.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] Even though the knowledge of many of the Higgs boson properties has advanced significantly since its discovery, the Higgs boson's self-coupling remains unmeasured.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] The shape of the Higgs potential in the Standard Model includes both trilinear and quartic self-couplings, which are key to understanding the complete shape of the potential and the nature of the Higgs field and EWSB.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] Higgs boson pair production offers a direct experimental probe of the self-coupling λ at the electroweak scale.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] Evidence for the Higgs field and its properties has been extremely significant for many reasons.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] Conversely, evidence that the Higgs field and boson did *not* exist within the expected mass range would have also been significant.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] The Higgs boson validates the Standard Model mechanism of mass generation for the weak bosons, and can provide masses to the fermions.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] As more precise measurements of its properties are made, more advanced extensions may be suggested or excluded.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] As experimental means to measure the Higgs field behaviour and interactions are developed, this fundamental field may be better understood.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] If the Higgs boson had not been discovered, the Standard Model would have needed to be modified or superseded.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] Related to this, it is a widely held belief among many physicists that there is likely to be "new" physics beyond the Standard Model, and the Standard Model will at some point be extended or superseded.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] Below an extremely high temperature, electroweak symmetry breaking causes the electroweak interaction to manifest in part as the short-ranged weak force, which is carried by massive gauge bosons.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] In the history of the universe, electroweak symmetry breaking is believed to have happened at about 1 picosecond (10−12 s) after the Big Bang, when the universe was at a temperature 159.5±1.5 GeV/*k*B.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] This symmetry breaking is required for atoms and other structures to form, as well as for nuclear reactions in stars, such as the Sun.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] The Higgs field is responsible for this symmetry breaking.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] The fermion masses must be entered by hand, essentially determining the relative strength of the coupling of the fermion to the Higgs field.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] The Higgs field does not "create" mass out of nothing, nor is the Higgs field responsible for the mass of all particles.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] In Higgs-based theories, the property of "mass" is a manifestation of potential energy transferred to fundamental particles when they interact ("couple") with the Higgs field.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] The Higgs field is the only scalar (spin-0) field to be detected; all the other fundamental fields in the Standard Model are spin-⁠ 1 /2⁠ fermions or spin-1 bosons.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] According to Rolf-Dieter Heuer, director general of CERN when the Higgs boson was discovered, this existence proof of a scalar field is almost as important as the Higgs's role in determining the mass of other particles.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] It suggests that other hypothetical scalar fields suggested by other theories, from the inflaton to quintessence, could perhaps exist as well.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] There has been considerable scientific research on possible links between the Higgs field and the inflaton – a hypothetical field suggested as the explanation for the expansion of space during the first fraction of a second of the universe (known as the "inflationary epoch").
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] Some theories suggest that a fundamental scalar field might be responsible for this phenomenon; the Higgs field is such a field, and its existence has led to papers analysing whether it could also be the *inflaton* responsible for this exponential expansion of the universe during the Big Bang.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] In the Standard Model, there exists the possibility that the underlying state of our universe – known as the "vacuum" – is long-lived, but not completely stable.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] In this scenario, the universe as we know it could effectively be destroyed by collapsing into a more stable vacuum state.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] This was sometimes misreported as the Higgs boson "ending" the universe.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] If the masses of the Higgs boson and top quark are known more precisely, and the Standard Model provides an accurate description of particle physics up to extreme energies of the Planck scale, then it is possible to calculate whether the vacuum is stable or merely long-lived.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] A Higgs mass of 125–127 GeV/*c*2 seems to be extremely close to the boundary for stability, but a definitive answer requires much more precise measurements of the pole mass of the top quark.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] It also suggests that the Higgs self-coupling λ and its βλ function could be very close to zero at the Planck scale, with "intriguing" implications, including theories of gravity and Higgs-based inflation.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] A future electron–positron collider would be able to provide the precise measurements of the top quark needed for such calculations.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] More speculatively, the Higgs field has also been proposed as the energy of the vacuum, which at the extreme energies of the first moments of the Big Bang caused the universe to be a kind of featureless symmetry of undifferentiated, extremely high energy.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] The relationship (if any) between the Higgs field and the observed vacuum energy density of the universe has also come under scientific study.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] As observed, the vacuum energy density is extremely close to zero, but the energy densities predicted from the Higgs field, supersymmetry, and other theories are typically many orders of magnitude larger.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] It is unclear how these should be reconciled.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p01] This cosmological constant problem remains a major unanswered problem in physics.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] Particle physicists study matter made from fundamental particles whose interactions are mediated by exchange particles – gauge bosons – acting as force carriers.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] However, attempts to produce quantum field models for two of the four known fundamental forces – the electromagnetic force and the weak nuclear force – and then to unify these interactions, were still unsuccessful.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] One known problem was that gauge invariant approaches, including non-abelian models such as Yang–Mills theory (1954), which held great promise for unified theories, also seemed to predict known massive particles as massless.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] Goldstone's theorem, relating to continuous symmetries within some theories, also appeared to rule out many obvious solutions, since it appeared to show that zero-mass particles known as Goldstone bosons would also have to exist that simply were "not seen".
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] According to Guralnik, physicists had "no understanding" how these problems could be overcome.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] The Higgs mechanism is a process by which vector bosons can acquire rest mass *without* explicitly breaking gauge invariance, as a byproduct of spontaneous symmetry breaking.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] Higgs also wrote a short, but important, response published in September 1964 to an objection by Gilbert, which showed that if calculating within the radiation gauge, Goldstone's theorem and Gilbert's objection would become inapplicable.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] Higgs later described Gilbert's objection as prompting his own paper.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] Properties of the model were further considered by Guralnik in 1965, by Higgs in 1966, by Kibble in 1967, and further by GHK in 1967.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] The original three 1964 papers demonstrated that when a gauge theory is combined with an additional charged scalar field that spontaneously breaks the symmetry, the gauge bosons may consistently acquire a finite mass.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] Weinberg was the first to observe that this would also provide mass terms for the fermions.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] At first, these seminal papers on spontaneous breaking of gauge symmetries were largely ignored, because it was widely believed that the (non-Abelian gauge) theories in question were a dead-end, and in particular that they could not be renormalised.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] In 1971–72, Martinus Veltman and Gerard 't Hooft proved renormalisation of Yang–Mills was possible in two papers covering massless, and then massive, fields.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] In practice, Politzer states, almost everyone learned of the theory due to physicist Benjamin Lee, who combined the work of Veltman and 't Hooft with insights by others, and popularised the completed theory.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] In this way, from 1971, interest and acceptance "exploded" and the ideas were quickly absorbed in the mainstream.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] The resulting electroweak theory and Standard Model have accurately predicted (among other things) weak neutral currents, three bosons, the top and charm quarks, and with great precision, the mass and other properties of some of these.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] Many of those involved eventually won Nobel Prizes or other renowned awards.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] By 1986 and again in the 1990s it became possible to write that understanding and proving the Higgs sector of the Standard Model was "the central problem today in particle physics".
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] The three papers written in 1964 were each recognised as milestone papers during *Physical Review Letters*'s 50th anniversary celebration.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] Their six authors were also awarded the 2010 J.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] Sakurai Prize for Theoretical Particle Physics for this work.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] Higgs's subsequent 1966 paper showed the decay mechanism of the boson; only a massive boson can decay and the decays can prove the mechanism.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] In the paper by Higgs the boson is massive, and in a closing sentence Higgs writes that "an essential feature" of the theory "is the prediction of incomplete multiplets of scalar and vector bosons".
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] Some versions of the theory predicted more than one kind of Higgs fields and bosons, and alternative "Higgsless" models were considered until the discovery of the Higgs boson.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] To produce Higgs bosons, two beams of particles are accelerated to very high energies and allowed to collide within a particle detector.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] Occasionally, although rarely, a Higgs boson will be created fleetingly as part of the collision byproducts.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] Because the Higgs boson decays very quickly, particle detectors cannot detect it directly.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] Instead the detectors register all the decay products (the *decay signature*) and from the data the decay process is reconstructed.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] If the observed decay products match a possible decay process (known as a *decay channel*) of a Higgs boson, this indicates that a Higgs boson may have been created.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] In practice, many processes may produce similar decay signatures.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] Fortunately, the Standard Model precisely predicts the likelihood of each of these, and each known process, occurring.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] So, if the detector detects more decay signatures consistently matching a Higgs boson than would otherwise be expected if Higgs bosons did not exist, then this would be strong evidence that the Higgs boson exists.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] More collision data allows better confirmation of the physical properties of any new particle observed, and allows physicists to decide whether it is indeed a Higgs boson as described by the Standard Model or some other hypothetical new particle.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] To find the Higgs boson, a powerful particle accelerator was needed, because Higgs bosons might not be seen in lower-energy experiments.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] The collider needed to have a high luminosity in order to ensure enough collisions were seen for conclusions to be drawn.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] Finally, advanced computing facilities were needed to process the vast amount of data (25 petabytes per year as of 2012) produced by the collisions.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] The first extensive search for the Higgs boson was conducted at the Large Electron–Positron Collider (LEP) at CERN in the 1990s.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] At the end of its service in 2000, LEP had found no conclusive evidence for the Higgs.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] This implied that if the Higgs boson were to exist it would have to be heavier than 114.4 GeV/*c*2.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] The search continued at Fermilab in the United States, where the Tevatron – the collider that discovered the top quark in 1995 – had been upgraded for this purpose.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] There was no guarantee that the Tevatron would be able to find the Higgs, but it was the only supercollider that was operational since the Large Hadron Collider (LHC) was still under construction and the planned Superconducting Super Collider had been cancelled in 1993 and never completed.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] The Tevatron was only able to exclude further ranges for the Higgs mass, and was shut down on 30 September 2011 because it no longer could keep up with the LHC.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] The final analysis of the data excluded the possibility of a Higgs boson with a mass between 147 GeV/*c*2 and 180 GeV/*c*2.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] In addition, there was a small (but not significant) excess of events possibly indicating a Higgs boson with a mass between 115 GeV/*c*2 and 140 GeV/*c*2.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] The Large Hadron Collider at CERN in Switzerland, was designed specifically to be able to either confirm or exclude the existence of the Higgs boson.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] Built in a 27 km tunnel under the ground near Geneva originally inhabited by LEP, it was designed to collide two beams of protons, initially at energies of 3.5 TeV per beam (7 TeV total), or almost 3.6 times that of the Tevatron, and upgradeable to 2 × 7 TeV (14 TeV total) in future.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] Theory suggested if the Higgs boson existed, collisions at these energy levels should be able to reveal it.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] Data collection at the LHC finally commenced in March 2010.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] By December 2011 the two main particle detectors at the LHC, ATLAS and CMS, had narrowed down the mass range where the Higgs could exist to around 116–130 GeV/*c*2 (ATLAS) and 115–127 GeV/*c*2 (CMS).
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] There had also already been a number of promising event excesses that had "evaporated" and proven to be nothing but random fluctuations.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] However, from around May 2011, both experiments had seen among their results, the slow emergence of a small yet consistent excess of gamma and 4-lepton decay signatures and several other particle decays, all hinting at a new particle at a mass around 125 GeV/*c*2.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] By around November 2011, the anomalous data at 125 GeV/*c*2 was becoming "too large to ignore" (although still far from conclusive), and the team leaders at both ATLAS and CMS each privately suspected they might have found the Higgs.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] It was therefore widely anticipated around the end of 2011, that the LHC would provide sufficient data to either exclude or confirm the finding of a Higgs boson by the end of 2012, when their 2012 collision data (with slightly higher 8 TeV collision energy) had been examined.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] On 4 July 2012 both of the CERN experiments announced they had independently made the same discovery: CMS of a previously unknown boson with mass 125.3±0.6 GeV/*c*2 and ATLAS of a boson with mass 126.0±0.6 GeV/*c*2.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] Using the combined analysis of two interaction types (known as 'channels'), both experiments independently reached a local significance of 5 sigma – implying that the probability of getting at least as strong a result by chance alone is less than one in three million.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] When additional channels were taken into account, the CMS significance was reduced to 4.9 sigma.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] The two teams had been working 'blinded' from each other from around late 2011 or early 2012, meaning they did not discuss their results with each other, providing additional certainty that any common finding was genuine validation of a particle.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] This level of evidence, confirmed independently by two separate teams and experiments, meets the formal level of proof required to announce a confirmed discovery.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] Following the 2012 discovery, it was still unconfirmed whether the 125 GeV/*c*2 particle was a Higgs boson.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] On one hand, observations remained consistent with the observed particle being the Standard Model Higgs boson, and the particle decayed into at least some of the predicted channels.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] Moreover, the production rates and branching ratios for the observed channels broadly matched the predictions by the Standard Model within the experimental uncertainties.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] However, the experimental uncertainties still left room for alternative explanations, meaning an announcement of the discovery of a Higgs boson would have been premature.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] To allow more opportunity for data collection, the LHC's proposed 2012 shutdown and 2013–14 upgrade were postponed by seven weeks into 2013.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] In November 2012, in a conference in Kyoto researchers said evidence gathered since July was falling into line with the basic Standard Model more than its alternatives, with a range of results for several interactions matching that theory's predictions.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] However some kinds of extensions to the Standard Model would also show very similar results; so commentators noted that based on other particles that are still being understood long after their discovery, it may take years to be sure, and decades to fully understand the particle that has been found.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] These findings meant that as of January 2013, scientists were very sure they had found an unknown particle of mass ~ 125 GeV/*c*2, and had not been misled by experimental error or a chance result.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] They were also sure, from initial observations, that the new particle was some kind of boson.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] The behaviours and properties of the particle, so far as examined since July 2012, also seemed quite close to the behaviours expected of a Higgs boson.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] Despite this, in late 2012, widespread media reports announced (incorrectly) that a Higgs boson had been confirmed during the year.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] In early March 2013, CERN Research Director Sergio Bertolucci stated that confirming spin-0 was the major remaining requirement to determine whether the particle is at least some kind of Higgs boson.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] This also makes the particle the first elementary scalar particle to be discovered in nature.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] In July 2017, CERN confirmed that all measurements still agree with the predictions of the Standard Model, and called the discovered particle simply "the Higgs boson".
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] As of 2019, the Large Hadron Collider has continued to produce findings that confirm the 2013 understanding of the Higgs field and particle.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] The LHC's experimental work since restarting in 2015 has included probing the Higgs field and boson to a greater level of detail, and confirming whether less common predictions were correct.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] Published results as of 19 March 2018 at 13 TeV for ATLAS and CMS had their measurements of the Higgs mass at 124.98±0.28 GeV/*c*2 and 125.26±0.21 GeV/*c*2 respectively.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] In July 2018, the ATLAS and CMS experiments reported observing the Higgs boson decay into a pair of bottom quarks, which makes up approximately 60% of all of its decays.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] Gauge invariance is an important property of modern particle theories such as the Standard Model, partly due to its success in other areas of fundamental physics such as electromagnetism and the strong interaction (quantum chromodynamics).
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] However, before Sheldon Glashow extended the electroweak unification models in 1961, there were great difficulties in developing gauge theories for the weak nuclear force or a possible unified electroweak interaction.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] Fermions with a mass term would violate gauge symmetry and therefore cannot be gauge invariant.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] Therefore, it seems that *none* of the standard model fermions *or* bosons could "begin" with mass as an inbuilt property except by abandoning gauge invariance.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] If gauge invariance were to be retained, then these particles had to be acquiring their mass by some other mechanism or interaction.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] Additionally, solutions based on spontaneous symmetry breaking appeared to fail, seemingly an inevitable result of Goldstone's theorem.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] Because there is no potential energy cost to moving around the complex plane's "circular valley" responsible for spontaneous symmetry breaking, the resulting quantum excitation is pure kinetic energy, and therefore a massless boson ("Goldstone boson"), which in turn implies a new long range force.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] But no new long range forces or massless particles were detected either.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] So whatever was giving these particles their mass had to not "break" gauge invariance as the basis for other parts of the theories where it worked well, *and* had to not require or predict unexpected massless particles or long-range forces which did not actually seem to exist in nature.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] This became known as the Higgs mechanism.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] The Standard Model hypothesises a field which is responsible for this effect, called the Higgs field (symbol: $\phi$ ), which has the unusual property of a non-zero amplitude in its ground state; i.e., a non-zero vacuum expectation value.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] It can have this effect because of its unusual "sombrero" shaped potential whose lowest "point" is not at its "centre".
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] In simple terms, unlike all other known fields, the Higgs field requires *less* energy to have a non-zero value than a zero value, so it ends up having a non-zero value *everywhere*.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] Below a certain extremely high energy level the existence of this non-zero vacuum expectation spontaneously breaks electroweak gauge symmetry which in turn gives rise to the Higgs mechanism and triggers the acquisition of mass by those particles interacting with the field.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] This effect occurs because scalar field components of the Higgs field are "absorbed" by the massive bosons as degrees of freedom, and couple to the fermions via Yukawa coupling, thereby producing the expected mass terms.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] When symmetry breaks under these conditions, the Goldstone bosons that arise *interact* with the Higgs field (and with other particles capable of interacting with the Higgs field) instead of becoming new massless particles.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] The intractable problems of both underlying theories "neutralise" each other, and the residual outcome is that elementary particles acquire a consistent mass based on how strongly they interact with the Higgs field.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] It is the simplest known process capable of giving mass to the gauge bosons while remaining compatible with gauge theories.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] Its quantum would be a scalar boson, known as the Higgs boson.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] The proposed Higgs mechanism arose as a result of theories proposed to explain observations in superconductivity.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] A superconductor does not allow penetration by external magnetic fields (the Meissner effect).
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] This strange observation implies that somehow, the electromagnetic field becomes short ranged during this phenomenon.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] Successful theories arose to explain this during the 1950s, first for fermions (Ginzburg–Landau theory, 1950), and then for bosons (BCS theory, 1957).
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] In these theories, superconductivity is interpreted as arising from a charged condensate field.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] Initially, the condensate value does not have any preferred direction, implying it is scalar, but its phase is capable of defining a gauge, in gauge based field theories.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] A charged scalar field must also be complex (or described another way, it contains at least two components, and a symmetry capable of rotating each into the other(s)).
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] In naïve gauge theory, a gauge transformation of a condensate usually rotates the phase.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] But in these circumstances, it instead fixes a preferred choice of phase.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] However, it turns out that fixing the choice of gauge so that the condensate has the same phase everywhere also causes the electromagnetic field to gain an extra term.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] This extra term causes the electromagnetic field to become short range.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] Once attention was drawn to this theory within particle physics, the parallels were clear.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] The features of a field required to do this were also quite well defined – it would have to be a charged scalar field, with at least two components, and complex in order to support a symmetry able to rotate these into each other.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] The Minimal Standard Model as described above is the simplest known model for the Higgs mechanism with just one Higgs field.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] However, an extended Higgs sector with additional Higgs particle doublets or triplets is also possible, and many extensions of the Standard Model have this feature.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] The non-minimal Higgs sector favoured by theory are the two-Higgs-doublet models (2HDM), which predict the existence of a quintet of scalar particles: two CP-even neutral Higgs bosons h0 and H0, a CP-odd neutral Higgs boson A0, and two charged Higgs particles H±.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] Supersymmetry ("SUSY") also predicts relations between the Higgs-boson masses and the masses of the gauge bosons, and could accommodate a 125 GeV/*c*2 neutral Higgs boson.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] The key method to distinguish between these different models involves study of the particles' interactions ("coupling") and exact decay processes ("branching ratios"), which can be measured and tested experimentally in particle collisions.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] In the Type-I 2HDM model one Higgs doublet couples to up and down quarks, while the second doublet does not couple to quarks.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] This model has two interesting limits, in which the lightest Higgs couples to just fermions ("gauge-phobic") or just gauge bosons ("fermiophobic"), but not both.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] In the Type-II 2HDM model, one Higgs doublet only couples to up-type quarks, the other only couples to down-type quarks.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] The heavily researched Minimal Supersymmetric Standard Model (MSSM) includes a Type-II 2HDM Higgs sector, so it could be disproven by evidence of a Type-I 2HDM Higgs.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] In other models the Higgs scalar is a composite particle.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] For example, in technicolour the role of the Higgs field is played by strongly bound pairs of fermions called techniquarks.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] Other models feature pairs of top quarks (see top quark condensate).
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] In yet other models, there is no Higgs field at all and the electroweak symmetry is broken using extra dimensions.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] The Standard Model leaves the mass of the Higgs boson as a parameter to be measured, rather than a value to be calculated.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] Reconciling these points appears to require explaining why there is an almost-perfect cancellation resulting in the visible mass of ~ 125 GeV/*c*2, and it is not clear how to do this.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] More broadly, the hierarchy problem amounts to the worry that a future theory of fundamental particles and interactions should not have excessive fine-tunings or unduly delicate cancellations, and should allow masses of particles such as the Higgs boson to be calculable.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] The problem is in some ways unique to spin-0 particles (such as the Higgs boson), which can give rise to issues related to quantum corrections that do not affect particles with spin.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] A number of solutions have been proposed, including supersymmetry, conformal solutions and solutions via extra dimensions such as braneworld models.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] There are also issues of quantum triviality, which suggests that it may not be possible to create a consistent quantum field theory involving elementary scalar particles.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p02] This can also lead to a predictable Higgs mass in asymptotic safety scenarios.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] In the Standard Model, the Higgs field is a scalar tachyonic field – *scalar* meaning it does not transform under Lorentz transformations, and *tachyonic* meaning the field (but **not** the particle) has imaginary mass, and in certain configurations must undergo symmetry breaking.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] It consists of four components: Two neutral ones and two charged component fields.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] Both of the charged components and one of the neutral fields are Goldstone bosons, which act as the longitudinal third-polarisation components of the massive W+, W−, and Z bosons.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] The quantum of the remaining neutral component corresponds to (and is theoretically realised as) the massive Higgs boson.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] This component can interact with fermions via Yukawa coupling to give them mass as well.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] Mathematically, the Higgs field has imaginary mass and is therefore a *tachyonic* field.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] While tachyons (particles that move faster than light) are a purely hypothetical concept, *fields* with imaginary mass have come to play an important role in modern physics.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] Under no circumstances do any excitations ever propagate faster than light in such theories – the presence or absence of a tachyonic mass has no effect whatsoever on the maximum velocity of signals (there is no violation of causality).
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] Instead of faster-than-light particles, the imaginary mass creates an instability: Any configuration in which one or more field excitations are tachyonic must spontaneously decay, and the resulting configuration contains no physical tachyons.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] This process is known as tachyon condensation, and is now believed to be the explanation for how the Higgs mechanism itself arises in nature, and therefore the reason behind electroweak symmetry breaking.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] Although the notion of imaginary mass might seem troubling, it is only the field, and not the mass itself, that is quantised.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] Therefore, the field operators at spacelike separated points still commute (or anticommute), and information and particles still do not propagate faster than light.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] Tachyon condensation drives a physical system that has reached a local limit – and might naively be expected to produce physical tachyons – to an alternate stable state where no physical tachyons exist.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] Once a tachyonic field such as the Higgs field reaches the minimum of the potential, its quanta are not tachyons any more but rather are ordinary particles such as the Higgs boson.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] Since the Higgs field is scalar, the Higgs boson has no spin.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] The Higgs boson is also its own antiparticle, is CP-even, and has zero electric and colour charge.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] The Standard Model does not predict the mass of the Higgs boson.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] If that mass is between 115 and 180 GeV/*c*2 (consistent with empirical observations of 125 GeV/*c*2), then the Standard Model can be valid at energy scales all the way up to the Planck scale (1019 GeV/*c*2).
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] It should be the only particle in the Standard Model that remains massive even at high energies.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] Many theorists expect new physics beyond the Standard Model to emerge at the TeV-scale, based on unsatisfactory properties of the Standard Model.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] The highest possible mass scale allowed for the Higgs boson (or some other electroweak symmetry breaking mechanism) is 1.4 TeV; beyond this point, the Standard Model becomes inconsistent without such a mechanism, because unitarity is violated in certain scattering processes.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] It is also possible, although experimentally difficult, to estimate the mass of the Higgs boson indirectly: In the Standard Model, the Higgs boson has a number of indirect effects; most notably, Higgs loops result in tiny corrections to masses of the W and Z bosons.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] Precision measurements of electroweak parameters, such as the Fermi constant and masses of the W and Z bosons, can be used to calculate constraints on the mass of the Higgs.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] As of July 2011, the precision electroweak measurements tell us that the mass of the Higgs boson is likely to be less than about 161 GeV/*c*2 at 95% confidence level.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] These indirect constraints rely on the assumption that the Standard Model is correct.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] It may still be possible to discover a Higgs boson above these masses, if it is accompanied by other particles beyond those accommodated by the Standard Model.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] The LHC cannot directly measure the Higgs boson's lifetime, due to its extreme brevity.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] It is predicted as 1.56×10−22 s based on the predicted decay width of 4.07×10−3 GeV.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] However it can be measured indirectly, based upon comparing masses measured from quantum phenomena occurring in the on shell production pathways and in the, much rarer, off shell production pathways, derived from Dalitz decay via a virtual photon (H → γ*γ → ℓℓγ).
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] Using this technique, the lifetime of the Higgs boson was tentatively measured in 2021 as 1.2 – 4.6×10−22 s, at sigma 3.2 (1 in 1000) significance.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] If Higgs particle theories are valid, then a Higgs particle can be produced much like other particles that are studied, in a particle collider.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] This involves accelerating a large number of particles to extremely high energies and extremely close to the speed of light, then allowing them to smash together.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] Protons and lead ions (the bare nuclei of lead atoms) are used at the LHC.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] In the extreme energies of these collisions, the desired esoteric particles will occasionally be produced and this can be detected and studied; any absence or difference from theoretical expectations can also be used to improve the theory.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] The relevant particle theory (in this case the Standard Model) will determine the necessary kinds of collisions and detectors.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] The Standard Model predicts that Higgs bosons could be formed in a number of ways, although the probability of producing a Higgs boson in any collision is always expected to be very small – for example, only one Higgs boson per 10 billion collisions in the Large Hadron Collider.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] Since the coupling of particles to the Higgs boson is proportional to their mass, this process is more likely for heavy particles.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] This process is the dominant contribution at the LHC and Tevatron being about ten times more likely than any of the other processes.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] – the two can merge to form a virtual W or Z boson which, if it carries sufficient energy, can then emit a Higgs boson.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] This process was the dominant production mode at the LEP, where an electron and a positron collided to form a virtual Z boson, and it was the second largest contribution for Higgs production at the Tevatron.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] At the LHC this process is only the third largest, because the LHC collides protons with protons, making a quark-antiquark collision less likely than at the Tevatron.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] Another possibility when two (anti-)fermions collide is that the two exchange a virtual W or Z boson, which emits a Higgs boson.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] The colliding fermions do not need to be the same type.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] may exchange a Z boson with an anti-down quark.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] This process is the second most important for the production of Higgs particle at the LHC and LEP.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] The final process that is commonly considered is by far the least likely (by two orders of magnitude).
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] This process involves two colliding gluons, which each decay into a heavy quark–antiquark pair.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] A quark and antiquark from each pair can then combine to form a Higgs particle.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] Quantum mechanics predicts that if it is possible for a particle to decay into a set of lighter particles, then it will eventually do so.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] The likelihood with which this happens depends on a variety of factors including: the difference in mass, the strength of the interactions, etc.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] Most of these factors are fixed by the Standard Model (SM), except for the mass of the Higgs boson itself.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] Given that the Higgs boson has a mass of 125 GeV/*c*2, the SM then predicts a mean life time of about 1.6×10−22 s.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] Since it interacts with all the massive elementary particles of the SM, the Higgs boson has many different processes through which it can decay.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] Each of these possible processes has its own probability, expressed as the *branching ratio*; the fraction of the total number decays that follows that process.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] The SM predicts these branching ratios as a function of the Higgs mass (see plot, right).
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] One way that the Higgs can decay is by splitting into a fermion–antifermion pair.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] As general rule, the Higgs is more likely to decay into heavy fermions than light fermions, because the mass of a fermion is proportional to the strength of its interaction with the Higgs.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] By this logic the most common decay should be into a top–antitop quark pair.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] However, such a decay would only be possible if the Higgs were heavier than ~346 GeV/*c*2, twice the mass of the top quark.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] Given a Higgs mass of 125 GeV/*c*2, the SM predicts that the most common decay is into a bottom–antibottom quark pair, which happens 57.7% of the time.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] The second most common fermion decay at that mass is a tau–antitau pair, which happens only about 6.3% of the time.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] Another possibility is for the Higgs to split into a pair of massive gauge bosons.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] The most likely possibility is for the Higgs to decay into a pair of W bosons (the light blue line in the plot), which happens about 21.5% of the time for a Higgs boson with a mass of 125 GeV/*c*2.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] The W bosons can subsequently decay either into a quark and an antiquark or into a charged lepton and a neutrino.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] The decays of W bosons into quarks are difficult to distinguish from the background, and the decays into leptons cannot be fully reconstructed (because neutrinos are impossible to detect in particle collision experiments).
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] A cleaner signal is given by decay into a pair of Z bosons (which happens about 2.6% of the time for a Higgs with a mass of 125 GeV/*c*2), if each of the bosons subsequently decays into a pair of easy-to-detect charged leptons (electrons or muons).
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] Decay into massless gauge bosons (i.e., gluons or photons) is also possible, but requires intermediate loop of virtual heavy quarks (top or bottom) or massive gauge bosons.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] The most common such process is the decay into a pair of gluons through a loop of virtual heavy quarks.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] This process, which is the reverse of the gluon fusion process mentioned above, happens approximately 8.6% of the time for a Higgs boson with a mass of 125 GeV/*c*2.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] Much rarer is the decay into a pair of photons mediated by a loop of W bosons or heavy quarks, which happens only twice for every thousand decays.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] However, this process is very relevant for experimental searches for the Higgs boson, because the energy and momentum of the photons can be measured very precisely, giving an accurate reconstruction of the mass of the decaying particle.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] In 2021 the extremely rare Dalitz decay was tentatively observed, into two leptons (electrons or muons) and a photon ( ℓℓγ ), via virtual photon decay.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] ATLAS searched for evidence of the first of these ( H → γ*γ → ℓℓγ ) for low lepton-pair masses ( ≤ 30 GeV/*c*2 ), where this process should dominate.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] The observation is at significance 3.2 sigma (1 chance in 1000 of being wrong).
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] This decay path is important because it facilitates measuring the on- and off-shell mass of the Higgs boson (allowing indirect measurement of decay time), and the decay into two charged particles allows exploration of charge conjugation and charge parity (CP) violation.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] Each of these production mechanisms offers different levels of sensitivity to the Higgs self-coupling λ, making them essential components in a comprehensive search for deviations from the Standard Model prediction.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] Higgs boson pairs can decay through various channels.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] The choice of decay mode affects the sensitivity of LHC experiments to the HH signal.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] The name most strongly associated with the particle and field is the Higgs boson and Higgs field.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] For some time the particle was known by a combination of its PRL author names (including at times Anderson), for example the Brout–Englert–Higgs particle, the Anderson–Higgs particle, or the Englert–Brout–Higgs–Guralnik–Hagen–Kibble mechanism, and these are still used at times.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] Fuelled in part by the issue of recognition and a potential shared Nobel Prize, the most appropriate name was still occasionally a topic of debate until 2013.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] Higgs himself preferred to call the particle either by an acronym of all those involved, or "the scalar boson", or "the so-called Higgs particle".
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] A considerable amount has been written on how Higgs's name came to be exclusively used.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] The first is that Higgs undertook a step which was either unique, clearer or more explicit in his paper in formally predicting and examining the particle.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] Of the PRL papers' authors, only the paper by Higgs *explicitly* offered as a prediction that a massive particle would exist and calculated some of its properties; he was therefore "the first to postulate the existence of a massive particle" according to *Nature*.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] In this way, Higgs's contribution also provided experimentalists with a crucial "concrete target" needed to test the theory.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] Higgs's paper also provided an "especially sharp" statement of the challenge and its solution according to science historian David Kaiser.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] The alternative explanation is that the name was popularised in the 1970s due to its use as a convenient shorthand or because of a mistake in citing.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] Many accounts (including Higgs's own) credit the "Higgs" name to physicist Benjamin Lee.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] Lee was a significant populariser of the theory in its early days, and habitually attached the name "Higgs" as a "convenient shorthand" for its components from 1972, and in at least one instance from as early as 1966.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] The Higgs boson is often referred to as the "God particle" in popular media outside the scientific community.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] The nickname comes from the title of the 1993 book on the Higgs boson and particle physics, *The God Particle: If the Universe Is the Answer, What Is the Question?* by Physics Nobel Prize winner and Fermilab director Leon M.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] The book sought in part to promote awareness of the significance and need for such a project in the face of its possible loss of funding.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] Higgs, an atheist, was reported to be displeased and stated in a 2008 interview that he found it "embarrassing" because it was "the kind of misuse [...] which I think might offend some people".
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] The nickname has been satirised in mainstream media as well.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] Science writer Ian Sample stated in his 2010 book on the search that the nickname is "universally hate[d]" by physicists and perhaps the "worst derided" in the history of physics, but that (according to Lederman) the publisher rejected all titles mentioning "Higgs" as unimaginative and too unknown.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] Lederman asks whether the Higgs boson was added just to perplex and confound those seeking knowledge of the universe, and whether physicists will be confounded by it as recounted in that story, or ultimately surmount the challenge and understand "how beautiful is the universe [God has] made".
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] So it's not an embarrassingly grandiose name, it is memorable, and [it] has some physics connection too." The name *Higgson* was suggested as well, in an opinion piece in the Institute of Physics' online publication *physicsworld.com*.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] An educational collaboration involving an LHC physicist and a High School Teachers at CERN educator suggests that dispersion of light – responsible for the rainbow and dispersive prism – is a useful analogy for the Higgs field's symmetry breaking and mass-causing effect.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] The Higgs field's effect on particles was famously described by physicist David Miller as akin to a room full of political party workers spread evenly throughout a room: The crowd gravitates to and slows down famous people but does not slow down others.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] He also drew attention to well-known effects in solid state physics where an electron's effective mass can be much greater than usual in the presence of a crystal lattice.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] The Higgs boson is commonly misunderstood as responsible for mass, rather than the Higgs field, and as relating to most mass in the universe.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] About 91% of the proton mass is due to the quark and gluon fields and the QCD conformal anomaly rather than the Higgs interaction.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] There was considerable discussion prior to late 2013 of how to allocate the credit if the Higgs boson is proven, made more pointed as a Nobel Prize had been expected, and the very wide basis of people entitled to consideration.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] The Nobel Prize has a limit of three persons to share an award, and some possible winners are already prize holders for other work, or are deceased (the prize is only awarded to persons in their lifetime).
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] Englert's co-researcher Robert Brout had died in 2011 and the Nobel Prize is not ordinarily given posthumously.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] Additionally *Physical Review Letters* 50-year review (2008) recognised the 1964 PRL symmetry breaking papers and Weinberg's 1967 paper *A model of Leptons* (the most cited paper in particle physics, as of 2012) "milestone Letters".
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] while the field has charge +⁠1/2⁠ under the weak hypercharge U(1) symmetry.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] The ground state of the Higgs field (the bottom of the potential) is degenerate with different ground states related to each other by a SU(2) gauge transformation.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] It is always possible to pick a gauge such that in the ground state $\phi ^{1}=\phi ^{2}=\phi ^{3}=0$ .
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] The expectation value of $\phi ^{0}$ in the ground state (the vacuum expectation value or VEV) is then $\left\langle \phi ^{0}\right\rangle ={\tfrac {1}{\sqrt {2\,}}}v$ , where $v={\tfrac {1}{\sqrt {\lambda \,}}}\left|\mu _{\text{H}}\right|$ .
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] The measured value of this parameter is ~246 GeV/*c*2.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] It has units of mass, and is the only free parameter of the Standard Model that is not a dimensionless number.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] where $(d,u,e,\nu )_{\text{L,R}}^{i}$ are left-handed and right-handed quarks and leptons of the ith generation, $\lambda _{\text{u,d,e}}^{i\,j}$ are matrices of Yukawa couplings where h.c. denotes the hermitian conjugate of all the preceding terms.
[src:standard-model/higgs-boson-p03] In the symmetry breaking ground state, only the terms containing $\phi ^{0}$ remain, giving rise to mass terms for the fermions.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] In theoretical physics, **quantum chromodynamics** (**QCD**) is the study of the strong interaction between quarks mediated by gluons.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Quarks are fundamental particles that make up composite hadrons such as the proton, neutron and pion.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] QCD is a type of quantum field theory called a non-abelian gauge theory, with symmetry group SU(3).
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] The QCD analog of electric charge is a property called *color*.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Gluons are the force carriers of the theory, just as photons are for the electromagnetic force in quantum electrodynamics.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] The theory is an important part of the Standard Model of particle physics.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] A large body of experimental evidence for QCD has been gathered over the years.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Physicist Murray Gell-Mann coined the word *quark* in its present sense.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] It originally comes from the phrase "Three quarks for Muster Mark" in *Finnegans Wake* by James Joyce.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] The three kinds of charge in QCD (as opposed to one in quantum electrodynamics or QED) are usually referred to as "color charge" by loose analogy to the three kinds of color (red, green and blue) perceived by humans.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Other than this nomenclature, the quantum parameter "color" is completely unrelated to the everyday, familiar phenomenon of color.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] The force between quarks is known as the **colour force** (or **color force**) or strong interaction, and is responsible for the nuclear force.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Since the theory of electric charge is dubbed "electrodynamics", the Greek word χρῶμα (*chrōma*, "color") is applied to the theory of color charge, "chromodynamics".
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] With the invention of bubble chambers and spark chambers in the 1950s, experimental particle physics discovered a large and ever-growing number of particles called hadrons.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] It seemed that such a large number of particles could not all be fundamental.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] First, the particles were classified by charge and isospin by Eugene Wigner and Werner Heisenberg; then, in 1953–56, according to strangeness by Murray Gell-Mann and Kazuhiko Nishijima (see Gell-Mann–Nishijima formula).
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] To gain greater insight, the hadrons were sorted into groups having similar properties and masses using the *eightfold way*, invented in 1961 by Gell-Mann and Yuval Ne'eman.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Gell-Mann and George Zweig, correcting an earlier approach of Shoichi Sakata, went on to propose in 1963 that the structure of the groups could be explained by the existence of three flavors of smaller particles inside the hadrons: the quarks.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Gell-Mann also briefly discussed a field theory model in which quarks interact with gluons.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Boris Struminsky was a PhD student of Nikolay Bogolyubov.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] The problem considered in this preprint was suggested by Nikolay Bogolyubov, who advised Boris Struminsky in this research.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] In the beginning of 1965, Nikolay Bogolyubov, Boris Struminsky and Albert Tavkhelidze wrote a preprint with a more detailed discussion of the additional quark quantum degree of freedom.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] This work was also presented by Albert Tavkhelidze without obtaining consent of his collaborators for doing so at an international conference in Trieste (Italy), in May 1965.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] A similar mysterious situation was with the Δ++ baryon; in the quark model, it is composed of three up quarks with parallel spins.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Greenberg; and Moo-Young Han and Yoichiru Nambu independently resolved the problem by proposing that quarks possess an additional SU(3) gauge degree of freedom, later called color charge.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Han and Nambu noted that quarks might interact via an octet of vector gauge bosons: the gluons.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] The meaning of this statement was usually clear in context: He meant quarks are confined, but he also was implying that the strong interactions could probably not be fully described by quantum field theory.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Richard Feynman argued that high energy experiments showed quarks are real particles: he called them *partons* (since they were parts of hadrons).
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] By particles, Feynman meant objects that travel along paths, elementary particles in a field theory.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] The difference between Feynman's and Gell-Mann's approaches reflected a deep split in the theoretical physics community.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Feynman thought the quarks have a distribution of position or momentum, like any other particle, and he (correctly) believed that the diffusion of parton momentum explained diffractive scattering.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Although Gell-Mann believed that certain quark charges could be localized, he was open to the possibility that the quarks themselves could not be localized because space and time break down.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] This was the more radical approach of S-matrix theory.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] James Bjorken proposed that pointlike partons would imply certain relations in deep inelastic scattering of electrons and protons, which were verified in experiments at SLAC in 1969.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] This led physicists to abandon the S-matrix approach for the strong interactions.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] In 1973 the concept of color as the source of a "strong field" was developed into the theory of QCD by physicists Harald Fritzsch and Heinrich Leutwyler, together with physicist Murray Gell-Mann.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] In particular, they employed the general field theory developed in 1954 by Chen Ning Yang and Robert Mills (see Yang–Mills theory), in which the carrier particles of a force can themselves radiate further carrier particles.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] The discovery of asymptotic freedom in the strong interactions by David Gross, David Politzer and Frank Wilczek allowed physicists to make precise predictions of the results of many high energy experiments using the quantum field theory technique of perturbation theory.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Evidence of gluons was discovered in three-jet events at PETRA in 1979.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] These experiments became more and more precise, culminating in the verification of perturbative QCD at the level of a few percent at LEP, at CERN.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] The other side of asymptotic freedom is confinement.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Since the force between color charges does not decrease with distance, it is believed that quarks and gluons can never be liberated from hadrons.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] This aspect of the theory is verified within lattice QCD computations, but is not mathematically proven.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] One of the Millennium Prize Problems announced by the Clay Mathematics Institute requires a claimant to produce such a proof.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Other aspects of non-perturbative QCD are the exploration of phases of quark matter, including the quark–gluon plasma.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Every field theory of particle physics is based on certain symmetries of nature whose existence is deduced from observations.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] QCD is a non-abelian gauge theory (or Yang–Mills theory) of the SU(3) gauge group obtained by taking the color charge to define a local symmetry.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Since the strong interaction does not discriminate between different flavors of quark, QCD has approximate **flavor symmetry**, which is broken by the differing masses of the quarks.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] There are additional global symmetries whose definitions require the notion of chirality, discrimination between left and right-handed.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] If the spin of a particle has a positive projection on its direction of motion then it is called right-handed; otherwise, it is left-handed.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Chirality and handedness are not the same, but become approximately equivalent at high energies.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] As mentioned, *asymptotic freedom* means that at large energy – this corresponds also to *short distances* – there is practically no interaction between the particles.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] This is in contrast – more precisely one would say *dual*– to what one is used to, since usually one connects the absence of interactions with *large* distances.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Here, in contrast to Wegner, we have only the dual model, which is that one described in this article.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] The color group SU(3) corresponds to the local symmetry whose gauging gives rise to QCD.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] The electric charge labels a representation of the local symmetry group U(1), which is gauged to give QED: this is an abelian group.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] If one considers a version of QCD with *Nf* flavors of massless quarks, then there is a global (chiral) flavor symmetry group SUL(*Nf*) × SUR(*Nf*) × UB(1) × UA(1).
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] The chiral symmetry is spontaneously broken by the QCD vacuum to the vector (L+R) SUV(*Nf*) with the formation of a chiral condensate.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] The vector symmetry, UB(1) corresponds to the baryon number of quarks and is an exact symmetry.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] The axial symmetry UA(1) is exact in the classical theory, but broken in the quantum theory, an occurrence called an anomaly.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Gluon field configurations called instantons are closely related to this anomaly.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] There are two different types of SU(3) symmetry: there is the symmetry that acts on the different colors of quarks, and this is an exact gauge symmetry mediated by the gluons, and there is also a flavor symmetry that rotates different flavors of quarks to each other, or *flavor SU(3)*.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Flavor SU(3) is an approximate symmetry of the vacuum of QCD, and is not a fundamental symmetry at all.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] It is an accidental consequence of the small mass of the three lightest quarks.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] In the QCD vacuum there are vacuum condensates of all the quarks whose mass is less than the QCD scale.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] This includes the up and down quarks, and to a lesser extent the strange quark, but not any of the others.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] The vacuum is symmetric under SU(2) isospin rotations of up and down, and to a lesser extent under rotations of up, down, and strange, or full flavor group SU(3), and the observed particles make isospin and SU(3) multiplets.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] The approximate flavor symmetries do have associated gauge bosons, observed particles like the rho and the omega, but these particles are nothing like the gluons and they are not massless.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] They are emergent gauge bosons in an approximate string description of QCD.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] The dynamics of the quarks and gluons are defined by the quantum chromodynamics Lagrangian.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] An explicit representation of these generators is given by $T_{a}=\lambda _{a}/2\,$ , wherein the $\lambda _{a}\,(a=1\ldots 8)\,$ are the Gell-Mann matrices.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] The symbol $G_{\mu \nu }^{a}\,$ represents the gauge invariant gluon field strength tensor, analogous to the electromagnetic field strength tensor, *F*μν, in quantum electrodynamics.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] where ${\mathcal {A}}_{\mu }^{a}(x)\,$ are the gluon fields, dynamical functions of spacetime, in the adjoint representation of the SU(3) gauge group, indexed by *a*, *b* and *c* running from 1 to 8 ; and *fabc* are the structure constants of SU(3) (the generators of the adjoint representation).
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Note that the rules to move-up or pull-down the *a*, *b*, or *c* indices are *trivial*, (+, ..., +), so that *fabc* = *fabc* = *f**a**bc* whereas for the *μ* or *ν* indices one has the non-trivial *relativistic* rules corresponding to the metric signature (+ − − −).
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] The variables *m* and *g* correspond to the quark mass and coupling of the theory, respectively, which are subject to renormalization.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] An important theoretical concept is the *Wilson loop* (named after Kenneth G.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] In lattice QCD, the final term of the above Lagrangian is discretized via Wilson loops, and more generally the behavior of Wilson loops can distinguish confined and deconfined phases.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Quarks are massive spin-1⁄2 fermions that carry a color charge whose gauging is the content of QCD.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Quarks are represented by Dirac fields in the fundamental representation **3** of the gauge group SU(3).
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] They also carry electric charge (either −1⁄3 or +2⁄3) and participate in weak interactions as part of weak isospin doublets.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] They carry global quantum numbers including the baryon number, which is 1⁄3 for each quark, hypercharge and one of the flavor quantum numbers.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Gluons are spin-1 bosons that also carry color charges, since they lie in the adjoint representation **8** of SU(3).
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] They have no electric charge, do not participate in the weak interactions, and have no flavor.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] They lie in the singlet representation **1** of all these symmetry groups.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Each type of quark has a corresponding antiquark, of which the charge is exactly opposite.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] They transform in the conjugate representation to quarks, denoted ${\bar {\mathbf {3} }}$ .
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] According to the rules of quantum field theory, and the associated Feynman diagrams, the above theory gives rise to three basic interactions: a quark may emit (or absorb) a gluon, a gluon may emit (or absorb) a gluon, and two gluons may directly interact.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] This contrasts with QED, in which only the first kind of interaction occurs, since photons have no charge.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Diagrams involving Faddeev–Popov ghosts must be considered too (except in the unitarity gauge).
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] This leads to *confinement* of the quarks to the interior of hadrons, i.e. mesons and nucleons, with typical radii *R*c, corresponding to former "Bag models" of the hadrons The order of magnitude of the "bag radius" is 1 fm (= 10−15 m).
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] For this behavior the non-abelian behavior of the gauge group is essential.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Further analysis of the content of the theory is complicated.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Various techniques have been developed to work with QCD.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Some of them are discussed briefly below.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] This approach is based on asymptotic freedom, which allows perturbation theory to be used accurately in experiments performed at very high energies.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Although limited in scope, this approach has resulted in the most precise tests of QCD to date.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Among non-perturbative approaches to QCD, the most well established is lattice QCD.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] While it is a slow and resource-intensive approach, it has wide applicability, giving insight into parts of the theory inaccessible by other means, in particular into the explicit forces acting between quarks and antiquarks in a meson.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] However, the numerical sign problem makes it difficult to use lattice methods to study QCD at high density and low temperature (e.g. nuclear matter or the interior of neutron stars).
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] A well-known approximation scheme, the 1⁄*N* expansion, starts from the idea that the number of colors is infinite, and makes a series of corrections to account for the fact that it is not.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Until now, it has been the source of qualitative insight rather than a method for quantitative predictions.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Modern variants include the AdS/CFT approach.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] For specific problems, effective theories may be written down that give qualitatively correct results in certain limits.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] In the best of cases, these may then be obtained as systematic expansions in some parameters of the QCD Lagrangian.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] One such effective field theory is chiral perturbation theory or ChiPT, which is the QCD effective theory at low energies.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] More precisely, it is a low energy expansion based on the spontaneous chiral symmetry breaking of QCD, which is an exact symmetry when quark masses are equal to zero, but for the u, d and s quark, which have small mass, it is still a good approximate symmetry.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Depending on the number of quarks that are treated as light, one uses either SU(2) ChiPT or SU(3) ChiPT.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Other effective theories are heavy quark effective theory (which expands around heavy quark mass near infinity), and soft-collinear effective theory (which expands around large ratios of energy scales).
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] In addition to effective theories, models like the Nambu–Jona-Lasinio model and the chiral model are often used when discussing general features.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Based on an Operator product expansion one can derive sets of relations that connect different observables with each other.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] The notion of quark flavors was prompted by the necessity of explaining the properties of hadrons during the development of the quark model.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] The notion of color was necessitated by the puzzle of the Δ++ .
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] This has been dealt with in the section on the history of QCD.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] The first evidence for quarks as real constituent elements of hadrons was obtained in deep inelastic scattering experiments at SLAC.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] The first evidence for gluons came in three-jet events at PETRA.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Quantitative tests of non-perturbative QCD are fewer, because the predictions are harder to make.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] The best is probably the running of the QCD coupling as probed through lattice computations of heavy-quarkonium spectra.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] There is a recent claim about the mass of the heavy meson Bc .
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Other non-perturbative tests are currently at the level of 5% at best.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Continuing work on masses and form factors of hadrons and their weak matrix elements are promising candidates for future quantitative tests.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] The whole subject of quark matter and the quark–gluon plasma is a non-perturbative test bed for QCD that still remains to be properly exploited.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] One qualitative prediction of QCD is that there exist composite particles made solely of gluons called glueballs that have not yet been definitively observed experimentally.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] A definitive observation of a glueball with the properties predicted by QCD would strongly confirm the theory.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] In principle, if glueballs could be definitively ruled out, this would be a serious experimental blow to QCD.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] But, as of 2013, scientists are unable to confirm or deny the existence of glueballs definitively, despite the fact that particle accelerators have sufficient energy to generate them.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] There are unexpected cross-relations to condensed matter physics.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] However, here the *coupling degrees of freedom* $J_{i,k}$ , which in the QCD correspond to the *gluons*, are "frozen" to fixed values (quenching).
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] In contrast, in the QCD they "fluctuate" (annealing), and through the large number of gauge degrees of freedom the entropy plays an important role (see below).
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] For positive *J*0 the thermodynamics of the Mattis spin glass corresponds in fact simply to a "ferromagnet in disguise", just because these systems have no "frustration" at all.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] This term is a basic measure in spin glass theory.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Quantitatively it is identical with the loop product $P_{W}:\,=\,J_{i,k}J_{k,l}...J_{n,m}J_{m,i}$ along a closed loop *W*.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] However, for a Mattis spin glass – in contrast to "genuine" spin glasses – the quantity *PW* never becomes negative.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] The basic notion "frustration" of the spin-glass is actually similar to the Wilson loop quantity of the QCD.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] The only difference is again that in the QCD one is dealing with SU(3) matrices, and that one is dealing with a "fluctuating" quantity.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Energetically, perfect absence of frustration should be non-favorable and atypical for a spin glass, which means that one should add the loop product to the Hamiltonian, by some kind of term representing a "punishment".
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] In the QCD the Wilson loop is essential for the Lagrangian rightaway.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] The relation between the QCD and "disordered magnetic systems" (the spin glasses belong to them) were additionally stressed in a paper by Fradkin, Huberman and Shenker, which also stresses the notion of duality.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] A further analogy consists in the already mentioned similarity to polymer physics, where, analogously to Wilson loops, so-called "entangled nets" appear, which are important for the formation of the entropy-elasticity (force proportional to the length) of a rubber band.
[src:standard-model/quantum-chromodynamics] Mathematically, this correspondendence is supported by the second term, $\propto gG_{\mu }^{a}{\bar {\psi }}_{i}\gamma ^{\mu }T_{ij}^{a}\psi _{j}\,,$ on the r.h.s. of the Lagrangian.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The **Standard Model** of particle physics is the theory describing three of the four known fundamental forces (electromagnetic, weak and strong interactions – excluding gravity) in the universe and classifying all known elementary particles.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] It was developed in stages throughout the latter half of the 20th century, through the work of many scientists worldwide, with the current formulation being finalized in the mid-1970s upon experimental confirmation of the existence of quarks.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Since then, proof of the top quark (1995), the tau neutrino (2000), and the Higgs boson (2012) have added further credence to the Standard Model.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] In addition, the Standard Model has predicted with great accuracy the various properties of weak neutral currents and the W and Z bosons.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Although the Standard Model is believed to be theoretically self-consistent and has demonstrated some success in providing experimental predictions, it leaves some physical phenomena unexplained and so falls short of being a complete theory of fundamental interactions.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] For example, it does not fully explain why there is more matter than anti-matter, incorporate the full theory of gravitation as described by general relativity, or account for the universe's accelerating expansion as possibly described by dark energy.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The model does not contain any viable dark matter particle that possesses all of the required properties deduced from observational cosmology.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The Standard Model without modifications also does not incorporate neutrino oscillations and their non-zero masses, but extensions have been proposed that can account for these features.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The development of the Standard Model was driven by theoretical and experimental particle physicists alike.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The Standard Model is a paradigm of a quantum field theory for theorists, exhibiting a wide range of phenomena, including spontaneous symmetry breaking, anomalies, and non-perturbative behavior.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] It is used as a basis for building more exotic models that incorporate hypothetical particles, extra dimensions, and elaborate symmetries (such as supersymmetry) to explain experimental results at variance with the Standard Model, such as the existence of dark matter and neutrino oscillations.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] In 1928, Paul Dirac introduced the Dirac equation, which implied the existence of antimatter.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] In 1954, Yang Chen-Ning and Robert Mills extended the concept of gauge theory for abelian groups, e.g. quantum electrodynamics, to nonabelian groups to provide an explanation for strong interactions.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] In 1957, Chien-Shiung Wu demonstrated parity was not conserved in the weak interaction.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] In 1961, Sheldon Glashow combined the electromagnetic and weak interactions.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] In 1964, Murray Gell-Mann and George Zweig introduced quarks and that same year Oscar W.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Greenberg implicitly introduced color charge of quarks.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] In 1967 Steven Weinberg and Abdus Salam incorporated the Higgs mechanism into Glashow's electroweak interaction, giving it its modern form.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] In 1970, Sheldon Glashow, John Iliopoulos, and Luciano Maiani introduced the GIM mechanism, predicting the charm quark.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] In 1973 Gross and Wilczek and Politzer independently discovered that non-Abelian gauge theories, like the color theory of the strong force, have asymptotic freedom.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] In 1971, Gerard 't Hooft showed that gauge theories, including Yang–Mills, could be renormalized.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] In 1976, Martin Perl discovered the tau lepton at the SLAC.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] In 1977, a team led by Leon Lederman at Fermilab discovered the bottom quark.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The Higgs mechanism is believed to give rise to the masses of all the elementary particles in the Standard Model.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] This includes the masses of the W and Z bosons, and the masses of the fermions, i.e. the quarks and leptons.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] After the neutral weak currents caused by Z boson exchange were discovered at CERN in 1973, the electroweak theory became widely accepted and Glashow, Salam, and Weinberg shared the 1979 Nobel Prize in Physics for discovering it.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The W± and Z0 bosons were discovered experimentally in 1983; and the ratio of their masses was found to be as the Standard Model predicted.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The term "Standard Model" was introduced by Abraham Pais and Sam Treiman in 1975, with reference to the electroweak theory with four quarks.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Steven Weinberg has since claimed priority, explaining that he chose the term Standard Model out of a sense of modesty and used it in 1973 during a talk in Aix-en-Provence in France.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The Standard Model includes members of several classes of elementary particles, which in turn can be distinguished by other characteristics, such as color charge.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The Standard Model includes 12 elementary particles of spin ⁠1/2⁠, known as fermions.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Fermions respect the Pauli exclusion principle, meaning that two identical fermions cannot simultaneously occupy the same quantum state in the same atom.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Each fermion has a corresponding antiparticle, which are particles that have corresponding properties with the exception of opposite charges.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Fermions are classified based on how they interact, which is determined by the charges they carry, into two groups: quarks and leptons.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Within each group, pairs of particles that exhibit similar physical behaviors are then grouped into generations (see the table).
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Each member of a generation has a greater mass than the corresponding particle of generations prior.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Thus, there are three generations of quarks and leptons.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] As first-generation particles do not decay, they comprise all of ordinary (baryonic) matter.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Specifically, all atoms consist of electrons orbiting around the atomic nucleus, ultimately constituted of up and down quarks.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] On the other hand, second- and third-generation charged particles decay with very short half-lives and can only be observed in high-energy environments.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Neutrinos of all generations also do not decay, and pervade the universe, but rarely interact with baryonic matter.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] There are six quarks: up, down, charm, strange, top, and bottom.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Quarks carry color charge, and hence interact via the strong interaction.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The color confinement phenomenon results in quarks being strongly bound together such that they form color-neutral composite particles called hadrons; quarks cannot individually exist and must always bind with other quarks.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Hadrons can contain either a quark-antiquark pair (mesons) or three quarks (baryons).
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The lightest baryons are the nucleons: the proton and neutron.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Quarks also carry electric charge and weak isospin, and thus interact with other fermions through electromagnetism and weak interaction.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The six leptons consist of the electron, electron neutrino, muon, muon neutrino, tau, and tau neutrino.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The leptons do not carry color charge, and do not respond to strong interaction.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The charged leptons carry an electric charge of −1 *e*, while the three neutrinos carry zero electric charge.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Thus, the neutrinos' motions are influenced by only the weak interaction and gravity, making them difficult to observe.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The Standard Model includes 4 kinds of gauge bosons of spin 1, with bosons being quantum particles containing an integer spin.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The gauge bosons are defined as force carriers, as they are responsible for mediating the fundamental interactions.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The Standard Model explains the four fundamental forces as arising from the interactions, with fermions exchanging virtual force carrier particles, thus mediating the forces.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] At a macroscopic scale, this manifests as a force.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] As a result, they do not follow the Pauli exclusion principle that constrains fermions; bosons do not have a theoretical limit on their spatial density.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The types of gauge bosons are described below.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] , responsible for interactions between electrically charged particles.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] They have no mass, and there are eight distinct gluons, with each being denoted through a color-anticolor charge combination (e.g. red–antigreen).
[src:standard-model/standard-model] As gluons have an effective color charge, they can also interact amongst themselves.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] carries an electric charge of +1 and −1 and couples to the electromagnetic interaction.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] boson interacts with both left-handed particles and right-handed antiparticles.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] , regarded as being the best explanation for gravity.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] In general relativity, gravity is explained as being the geometric curving of spacetime.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The Feynman diagram calculations, which are a graphical representation of the perturbation theory approximation, invoke "force mediating particles", and when applied to analyze high-energy scattering experiments are in reasonable agreement with the data.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] However, perturbation theory (and with it the concept of a "force-mediating particle") fails in other situations.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] These include low-energy quantum chromodynamics, bound states, and solitons.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The interactions between all the particles described by the Standard Model are summarized by the diagrams on the right of this section.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The Higgs particle is a massive scalar elementary particle theorized by Peter Higgs (and others) in 1964, when he showed that Goldstone's 1962 theorem (generic continuous symmetry, which is spontaneously broken) provides a third polarization of a massive vector field.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Hence, Goldstone's original scalar doublet, the massive spin-zero particle, was proposed as the Higgs boson, and is a key building block in the Standard Model.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] It has no intrinsic spin, and for that reason is classified as a boson with spin-0.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The Higgs boson plays a unique role in the Standard Model, by explaining why the other elementary particles, except the photon and gluon, are massive.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] In particular, the Higgs boson explains why the photon has no mass, while the W and Z bosons are very heavy.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Elementary-particle masses and the differences between electromagnetism (mediated by the photon) and the weak force (mediated by the W and Z bosons) are critical to many aspects of the structure of microscopic (and hence macroscopic) matter.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] In electroweak theory, the Higgs boson generates the masses of the leptons (electron, muon, and tau) and quarks.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] As the Higgs boson is massive, it must interact with itself.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Because the Higgs boson is a very massive particle and also decays almost immediately when created, only a very high-energy particle accelerator can observe and record it.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Experiments to confirm and determine the nature of the Higgs boson using the Large Hadron Collider (LHC) at CERN began in early 2010 and were performed at Fermilab's Tevatron until its closure in late 2011.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] On 4 July 2012, two of the experiments at the LHC (ATLAS and CMS) both reported independently that they had found a new particle with a mass of about 125 GeV/*c*2 (about 133 proton masses, on the order of 10−25 kg), which is "consistent with the Higgs boson".
[src:standard-model/standard-model] On 13 March 2013, it was confirmed to be the searched-for Higgs boson.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Technically, quantum field theory provides the mathematical framework for the Standard Model, in which a Lagrangian controls the dynamics and kinematics of the theory.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Each kind of particle is described in terms of a dynamical field that pervades space-time.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The global Poincaré symmetry is postulated for all relativistic quantum field theories.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] It consists of the familiar translational symmetry, rotational symmetry and the inertial reference frame invariance central to the theory of special relativity.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The local SU(3) × SU(2) × U(1) gauge symmetry is an internal symmetry that essentially defines the Standard Model.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Roughly, the three factors of the gauge symmetry give rise to the three fundamental interactions.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The fields fall into different representations of the various symmetry groups of the Standard Model (see table).
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Upon writing the most general Lagrangian, one finds that the dynamics depends on 19 parameters, whose numerical values are established by experiment.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The parameters are summarized in the table (made visible by clicking "show") above.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The quantum chromodynamics (QCD) sector defines the interactions between quarks and gluons, which is a Yang–Mills gauge theory with SU(3) symmetry, generated by $T^{a}=\lambda ^{a}/2$ .
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Since leptons do not interact with gluons, they are not affected by this sector.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Notice that the addition of fermion mass terms into the electroweak Lagrangian is forbidden, since terms of the form $m{\overline {\psi }}\psi$ do not respect U(1) × SU(2)L gauge invariance.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Neither is it possible to add explicit mass terms for the U(1) and SU(2) gauge fields.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The Higgs mechanism is responsible for the generation of the gauge boson masses, and the fermion masses result from Yukawa-type interactions with the Higgs field.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The weak hypercharge $Y_{\text{W}}$ of both components is 1.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Before symmetry breaking, the Higgs Lagrangian is ${\mathcal {L}}_{\text{H}}=\left(D_{\mu }\varphi \right)^{\dagger }\left(D^{\mu }\varphi \right)-V(\varphi ),$ where $D_{\mu }$ is the electroweak gauge covariant derivative defined above and $V(\varphi )$ is the potential of the Higgs field.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The square of the covariant derivative leads to three and four point interactions between the electroweak gauge fields $W_{\mu }^{a}$ and $B_{\mu }$ and the scalar field $\varphi$ .
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The quartic term describes self-interactions of the scalar field $\varphi$ .
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The minimum of the potential is degenerate with an infinite number of equivalent ground state solutions, which occurs when $\varphi ^{\dagger }\varphi ={\tfrac {\mu ^{2}}{2\lambda }}$ .
[src:standard-model/standard-model] It is possible to perform a gauge transformation on $\varphi$ such that the ground state is transformed to a basis where $\varphi _{1}=\varphi _{2}=\varphi _{4}=0$ and $\varphi _{3}={\tfrac {\mu }{\sqrt {\lambda }}}\equiv v$ .
[src:standard-model/standard-model] This breaks the symmetry of the ground state.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The expectation value of $\varphi$ now becomes $\langle \varphi \rangle ={\frac {1}{\sqrt {2}}}{\begin{pmatrix}0\\v\end{pmatrix}},$ where v has units of mass and sets the scale of electroweak physics.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] This is the only dimensional parameter of the Standard Model and has a measured value of ~246 GeV/*c*2.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] After symmetry breaking, the masses of the W and Z are given by $m_{\text{W}}={\frac {1}{2}}gv$ and $m_{\text{Z}}={\frac {1}{2}}{\sqrt {g^{2}+g'^{2}}}v$ , which can be viewed as predictions of the theory.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Since $\mu$ and $\lambda$ are free parameters, the Higgs's mass could not be predicted beforehand and had to be determined experimentally.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The fields $Q_{\text{L}}$ and $\ell _{\text{L}}$ are left-handed quark and lepton doublets.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Likewise, $u_{\text{R}},d_{\text{R}}$ and $e_{\text{R}}$ are right-handed up-type quark, down-type quark, and lepton singlets.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Finally $\varphi$ is the Higgs doublet and ${\tilde {\varphi }}=i\tau _{2}\varphi ^{*}$ is its charge conjugate state.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The Yukawa terms are invariant under the SU(2)L × U(1)Y gauge symmetry of the Standard Model and generate masses for all fermions after spontaneous symmetry breaking.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The Standard Model describes three of the four fundamental interactions in nature; only gravity remains unexplained.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] In the Standard Model, such an interaction is described as an exchange of bosons between the objects affected, such as a photon for the electromagnetic force and a gluon for the strong interaction.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Those particles are called force carriers or messenger particles.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Despite being perhaps the most familiar fundamental interaction, gravity is not described by the Standard Model, due to contradictions that arise when combining general relativity—the modern theory of gravity—and quantum mechanics.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] However, gravity is so weak at microscopic scales, that it is essentially unmeasurable.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The graviton is postulated to be the mediating particle, but has not yet been proved to exist.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Electromagnetism is the only long-range force in the Standard Model.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] It is mediated by photons and couples to electric charge.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Electromagnetism is responsible for a wide range of phenomena including atomic electron shell structure, chemical bonds, electric circuits and electronics.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Electromagnetic interactions in the Standard Model are described by quantum electrodynamics.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The weak interaction is responsible for various forms of particle decay, such as beta decay.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] It is weak and short-range, due to the fact that the weak mediating particles, W and Z bosons, have mass.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] W bosons have electric charge and mediate interactions that change the particle type (referred to as flavor) and charge.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Interactions mediated by W bosons are charged current interactions.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Z bosons are neutral and mediate neutral current interactions, which do not change particle flavor.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Thus Z bosons are similar to the photon, aside from them being massive and interacting with the neutrino.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The weak interaction is also the only interaction to violate parity and CP.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Parity violation is maximal for charged current interactions, since the W boson interacts exclusively with left-handed fermions and right-handed antifermions.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] In the Standard Model, the weak force is understood in terms of the electroweak theory, which states that the weak and electromagnetic interactions become united into a single *electroweak* interaction at high energies.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The strong interaction is responsible for hadronic and nuclear binding.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] It is mediated by gluons, which couple to color charge.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Since gluons themselves have color charge, the strong force exhibits confinement and asymptotic freedom.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Confinement means that only color-neutral particles can exist in isolation, therefore quarks can only exist in hadrons and never in isolation, at low energies.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Asymptotic freedom means that the strong force becomes weaker, as the energy scale increases.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The strong force overpowers the electrostatic repulsion of protons and quarks in nuclei and hadrons respectively, at their respective scales.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] While quarks are bound in hadrons by the fundamental strong interaction, which is mediated by gluons, nucleons are bound by an emergent phenomenon termed the *residual strong force* or *nuclear force*.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] This interaction is mediated by mesons, such as the pion.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The color charges inside the nucleon cancel out, meaning most of the gluon and quark fields cancel out outside of the nucleon.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] However, some residue is "leaked", which appears as the exchange of virtual mesons, which result in an effective attractive force between nucleons.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The (fundamental) strong interaction is described by quantum chromodynamics, which is a component of the Standard Model.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The Standard Model predicted the existence of the W and Z bosons, gluon, top quark and charm quark, and predicted many of their properties before these particles were observed.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The predictions were experimentally confirmed with good precision.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] The Standard Model also predicted the existence of the Higgs boson, which was found in 2012 at the Large Hadron Collider, the final fundamental particle predicted by the Standard Model to be experimentally confirmed.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Self-consistency of the Standard Model (currently formulated as a non-abelian gauge theory quantized through path-integrals) has not been mathematically proved.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] While regularized versions useful for approximate computations (for example lattice gauge theory) exist, it is not known whether they converge (in the sense of S-matrix elements) in the limit that the regulator is removed.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] A key question related to the consistency is the Yang–Mills existence and mass gap problem.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Experiments indicate that neutrinos have mass, which the classic Standard Model did not allow.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] To accommodate this finding, the classic Standard Model can be modified to include neutrino mass, although it is not obvious exactly how this should be done.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] If one insists on using only Standard Model particles, this can be achieved by adding a non-renormalizable interaction of leptons with the Higgs boson.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] On a fundamental level, such an interaction emerges in the seesaw mechanism where heavy right-handed neutrinos are added to the theory.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] This is natural in the left-right symmetric extension of the Standard Model and in certain grand unified theories.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] As long as new physics appears below or around 1014 GeV, the neutrino masses can be of the right order of magnitude.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Theoretical and experimental research has attempted to extend the Standard Model into a unified field theory or a theory of everything, a complete theory explaining all physical phenomena including constants.
[src:standard-model/standard-model] Currently, no proposed theory of everything has been widely accepted or verified.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] In nuclear physics and particle physics, the **strong interaction**, also called the **strong force** or **strong nuclear force**, is one of the four known fundamental interactions.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] It confines quarks into protons, neutrons, and other hadron particles, and also binds neutrons and protons to create atomic nuclei, where it is called the nuclear force.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] Most of the mass of a proton or neutron is the result of the strong interaction energy; the individual quarks provide only about 1% of the mass of a proton.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] At the range of 10−15 m (1 femtometer, slightly more than the radius of a nucleon), the strong force is approximately 100 times as strong as electromagnetism, 106 times as strong as the weak interaction, and 1038 times as strong as gravitation.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] In the context of atomic nuclei, the force binds protons and neutrons together to form a nucleus and is called the nuclear force (or *residual strong force*).
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] Because the force is mediated by massive, short lived mesons on this scale, the residual strong interaction obeys a distance-dependent behavior between nucleons that is quite different from when it is acting to bind quarks within hadrons.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] There are also differences in the binding energies of the nuclear force with regard to nuclear fusion versus nuclear fission.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] Nuclear fusion accounts for most energy production in the Sun and other stars.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] Nuclear fission allows for decay of radioactive elements and isotopes, although it is often mediated by the weak interaction.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] Artificially, the energy associated with the nuclear force is partially released in nuclear power and nuclear weapons, both in uranium or plutonium-based fission weapons and in fusion weapons like the hydrogen bomb.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] Before 1971, physicists were uncertain as to how the atomic nucleus was bound together.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] It was known that the nucleus was composed of protons and neutrons and that protons possessed positive electric charge, while neutrons were electrically neutral.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] Based on established principles of electromagnetism, positive charges would be expected to repel one another and the positively charged protons would be expected to cause the nucleus to fly apart.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] New discoveries in physics were needed to explain this phenomenon.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] A stronger attractive force was postulated to explain how the atomic nucleus was bound despite the protons' mutual electromagnetic repulsion.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] This hypothesized force was called the *strong force*, which was believed to be a fundamental force that acted on the protons and neutrons that make up the nucleus.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] In 1964, Murray Gell-Mann, and separately George Zweig, proposed that baryons, which include protons and neutrons, and mesons were composed of elementary particles.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] Zweig called the elementary particles "aces" while Gell-Mann called them "quarks"; the theory came to be called the quark model.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] The strong attraction between nucleons was the side-effect of a more fundamental force that bound the quarks together into protons and neutrons.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] The theory of quantum chromodynamics explains that quarks carry what is called a color charge, although it has no relation to visible color.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] Quarks with unlike color charge attract one another as a result of the strong interaction, and the particle that mediates this was called the gluon.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] The strong interaction is observable at two ranges, and mediated by different force carriers in each one.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] On a scale less than about 0.8 fm (roughly the radius of a nucleon), the force is carried by gluons and holds quarks together to form protons, neutrons, and other hadrons.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] On a larger scale, up to about 3 fm, the force is carried by mesons and binds nucleons (protons and neutrons) together to form the nucleus of an atom.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] In the former context, it is often known as the **color force**, and is so strong that if hadrons are struck by high-energy particles, they produce jets of massive particles instead of emitting their constituents (quarks and gluons) as freely moving particles.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] This property of the strong force is called color confinement.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] The word *strong* is used since the strong interaction is the "strongest" of the four fundamental forces.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] At a distance of 10−15 m, its strength is around 100 times that of the electromagnetic force, some 106 times as great as that of the weak force, and about 1038 times that of gravitation.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] The strong force is described by quantum chromodynamics (QCD), a part of the Standard Model of particle physics.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] Mathematically, QCD is a non-abelian gauge theory based on a local (gauge) symmetry group called SU(3).
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] The force carrier particle of the strong interaction is the gluon, a massless gauge boson.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] Gluons are thought to interact with quarks and other gluons by way of a type of charge called color charge.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] Color charge is analogous to electromagnetic charge, but it comes in three types (±red, ±green, and ±blue) rather than one, which results in different rules of behavior.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] These rules are described by quantum chromodynamics (QCD), the theory of quark–gluon interactions.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] Unlike the photon in electromagnetism, which is neutral, the gluon carries a color charge.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] Quarks and gluons are the only fundamental particles that carry non-vanishing color charge, and hence they participate in strong interactions only with each other.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] The strong force is the expression of the gluon interaction with other quark and gluon particles.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] All quarks and gluons in QCD interact with each other through the strong force.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] The strength of interaction is parameterized by the strong coupling constant.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] This strength is modified by the gauge color charge of the particle, a group-theoretical property.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] Unlike all other forces (electromagnetic, weak, and gravitational), the strong force does not diminish in strength with increasing distance between pairs of quarks.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] After a limiting distance (about the size of a hadron) has been reached, it remains at a strength of about 10000 N, no matter how much farther the distance between the quarks.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] As the separation between the quarks grows, the energy added to the pair creates new pairs of matching quarks between the original two; hence it is impossible to isolate quarks.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] The explanation is that the amount of work done against a force of 10000 N is enough to create particle–antiparticle pairs within a very short distance.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] The energy added to the system by pulling two quarks apart would create a pair of new quarks that will pair up with the original ones.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] In QCD, this phenomenon is called color confinement; as a result, only hadrons, not individual free quarks, can be observed.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] The failure of all experiments that have searched for free quarks is considered to be evidence of this phenomenon.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] The elementary quark and gluon particles involved in a high energy collision are not directly observable.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] The interaction produces jets of newly created hadrons that are observable.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] Those hadrons are created, as a manifestation of mass–energy equivalence, when sufficient energy is deposited into a quark–quark bond, as when a quark in one proton is struck by a very fast quark of another impacting proton during a particle accelerator experiment.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] However, quark–gluon plasmas have been observed.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] While color confinement implies that the strong force acts without distance-diminishment between pairs of quarks in compact collections of bound quarks (hadrons), at distances approaching or greater than the radius of a proton, a residual force (described below) remains.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] It manifests as a force between the "colorless" hadrons, and is known as the *nuclear force* or *residual strong force* (and historically as the *strong nuclear force*).
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] The nuclear force acts between hadrons, known as mesons and baryons.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] This "residual strong force", acting indirectly, transmits gluons that form part of the virtual π and ρ mesons, which, in turn, transmit the force between nucleons that holds the nucleus (beyond hydrogen-1 nucleus) together.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] The residual strong force is thus a minor residuum of the strong force that binds quarks together into protons and neutrons.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] Unlike the strong force, the residual strong force diminishes with distance, and does so rapidly.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] The decrease is approximately as a negative exponential power of distance, though there is no simple expression known for this; see *Yukawa potential*.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] The rapid decrease with distance of the attractive residual force and the less rapid decrease of the repulsive electromagnetic force acting between protons within a nucleus, causes the instability of larger atomic nuclei, such as all those with atomic numbers larger than 82 (the element lead).
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] Although the nuclear force is weaker than the strong interaction itself, it is still highly energetic: transitions produce gamma rays.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] The mass of a nucleus is significantly different from the summed masses of the individual nucleons.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] This mass defect is due to the potential energy associated with the nuclear force.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] Differences between mass defects power nuclear fusion and nuclear fission.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] The so-called Grand Unified Theories (GUT) aim to describe the strong interaction and the electroweak interaction as aspects of a single force, similarly to how the electromagnetic and weak interactions were unified by the Glashow–Weinberg–Salam model into electroweak interaction.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] The strong interaction has a property called asymptotic freedom, wherein the strength of the strong force diminishes at higher energies (or temperatures).
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] The theorized energy where its strength becomes equal to the electroweak interaction is the grand unification energy.
[src:standard-model/strong-interaction] However, no Grand Unified Theory has yet been successfully formulated to describe this process, and Grand Unification remains an unsolved problem in physics.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] In nuclear physics and particle physics, the **weak interaction**, **weak force** or **weak nuclear force**, is one of the four known fundamental interactions, with the others being electromagnetism, the strong interaction, and gravitation.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] It is the mechanism of interaction between subatomic particles that is responsible for the radioactive beta decay of atoms: The weak interaction participates in nuclear fission and nuclear fusion.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] The theory describing its behaviour and effects is sometimes called **quantum flavordynamics** (**QFD**); however, the term QFD is rarely used, because the weak force is better understood by electroweak theory (EWT).
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] The effective range of the weak force is limited to subatomic distances and is less than the diameter of a proton.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] The Standard Model of particle physics provides a uniform framework for understanding electromagnetic, weak, and strong interactions.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] An interaction occurs when two particles (typically, but not necessarily, half-integer spin fermions) exchange integer-spin, force-carrying bosons.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] The fermions involved in such exchanges can be either elementary (e.g., electrons or quarks) or composite (e.g., protons or neutrons), although at the deepest levels, all weak interactions ultimately are between elementary particles.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] In the weak interaction, fermions can exchange three types of force carriers, namely W+, W−, and Z bosons.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] The masses of these bosons are far greater than the mass of a proton or neutron, which is consistent with the short range of the weak force.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] In fact, the force is termed *weak* because its field strength over any set distance is typically several orders of magnitude less than that of the electromagnetic force, which itself is further orders of magnitude less than the strong nuclear force.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] The weak interaction is the only fundamental interaction that breaks parity symmetry, and similarly, but far more rarely, the only interaction to break charge–parity symmetry.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] Quarks, which make up composite particles like neutrons and protons, come in six "flavours" – up, down, charm, strange, top, and bottom – which give those composite particles their properties.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] The weak interaction is unique in that it allows quarks to swap their flavour for another.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] The swapping of those properties is mediated by the force-carrier bosons.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] For example, during beta-minus decay, a down quark within a neutron is changed into an up quark, thus converting the neutron to a proton and resulting in the emission of an electron and an electron antineutrino.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] Weak interaction is important in the fusion of hydrogen into helium in a star.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] This is because it can convert a proton (hydrogen) into a neutron that can fuse with another proton to form deuterium, which is important for the continuation of nuclear fusion to form helium.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] The accumulation of neutrons facilitates the buildup of heavy nuclei in a star.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] Most fermions decay by a weak interaction over time.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] Such decay makes radiocarbon dating possible, as carbon-14 decays through the weak interaction to nitrogen-14.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] It can also create radioluminescence, commonly used in tritium luminescence, and in the related field of betavoltaics (but *not* similar to radium luminescence).
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] The electroweak force is believed to have separated into the electromagnetic and weak forces during the quark epoch of the early universe.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] In 1933, Enrico Fermi proposed the first theory of the weak interaction, known as Fermi's interaction.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] He suggested that beta decay could be explained by a four-fermion interaction, involving a contact force with no range.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] In the mid-1950s, Chen-Ning Yang and Tsung-Dao Lee first suggested that the handedness of the spins of particles in weak interaction might violate the conservation law or symmetry.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] In 1957, the Wu experiment, carried out by Chien Shiung Wu and collaborators confirmed the symmetry violation.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] In the 1960s, Sheldon Glashow, Abdus Salam and Steven Weinberg unified the electromagnetic force and the weak interaction by showing them to be two aspects of a single force, now termed the electroweak force.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] The existence of the W and Z bosons was not directly confirmed until 1983.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] Due to their large mass (approximately 90 GeV/*c*2) these carrier particles, called the W and Z bosons, are short-lived with a lifetime of under 10−24 seconds.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] The weak interaction has a very short effective range (around 10−17 to 10−16 m (0.01 to 0.1 fm)).
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] At distances around 10−18 meters (0.001 fm), the weak interaction has an intensity of a similar magnitude to the electromagnetic force, but this starts to decrease exponentially with increasing distance.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] Scaled up by just one and a half orders of magnitude, at distances of around 3×10−17 m, the weak interaction becomes 10,000 times weaker.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] The weak interaction affects all the fermions of the Standard Model, as well as the Higgs boson; neutrinos interact only through gravity and the weak interaction.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] The weak interaction does not produce bound states, nor does it involve binding energy – something that gravity does on an astronomical scale, the electromagnetic force does at the molecular and atomic levels, and the strong nuclear force does only at the subatomic level, inside of nuclei.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] Its most noticeable effect is due to its first unique feature: The charged weak interaction causes flavour change.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] For example, a neutron is heavier than a proton (its partner nucleon) and can decay into a proton by changing the flavour (type) of one of its two *down* quarks to an *up* quark.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] All mesons are unstable because of weak decay.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] In the process known as beta decay, a *down* quark in the neutron can change into an *up* quark by emitting a virtual W− boson, which then decays into an electron and an electron antineutrino.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] Another example is electron capture – a common variant of radioactive decay – wherein a proton and an electron within an atom interact and are changed to a neutron (an up quark is changed to a down quark), and an electron neutrino is emitted.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] Due to the large masses of the W bosons, particle transformations or decays (e.g., flavour change) that depend on the weak interaction typically occur much more slowly than transformations or decays that depend only on the strong or electromagnetic forces.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] For example, a neutral pion decays electromagnetically, and so has a life of only about 10−16 seconds.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] In contrast, a charged pion can only decay through the weak interaction, and so lives about 10−8 seconds, or a hundred million times longer than a neutral pion.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] A particularly extreme example is the weak-force decay of a free neutron, which takes about 15 minutes.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] All right-handed (regular) particles and left-handed antiparticles have weak isospin of 0.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] All particles have a property called *weak isospin* (symbol T3), which serves as an additive quantum number that restricts how the particle can interact with the W± of the weak force.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] Weak isospin plays the same role in the weak interaction with W± as electric charge does in electromagnetism, and color charge in the strong interaction; a different number with a similar name, *weak charge*, discussed below, is used for interactions with the Z0 .
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] All left-handed fermions have a weak isospin value of either ⁠++1/2⁠ or ⁠−+1/2⁠; all right-handed fermions have 0 isospin.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] For example, the up quark has T3 = ⁠++1/2⁠ and the down quark has T3 = ⁠−+1/2⁠.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] A quark never decays through the weak interaction into a quark of the same T3: Quarks with a T3 of ⁠++1/2⁠ only decay into quarks with a T3 of ⁠−+1/2⁠ and conversely.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] In any given strong, electromagnetic, or weak interaction, weak isospin is conserved: The sum of the weak isospin numbers of the particles entering the interaction equals the sum of the weak isospin numbers of the particles exiting that interaction.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] For example, a (left-handed) π+ , with a weak isospin of +1 normally decays into a ν μ (with T3 = ⁠++1/2⁠) and a μ+ (as a right-handed antiparticle, ⁠++1/2⁠).
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] where YW is the weak hypercharge of a particle with electrical charge Q (in elementary charge units) and weak isospin T3.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] Weak hypercharge is the generator of the U(1) component of the electroweak gauge group; whereas some particles have a weak isospin of zero, all known spin-⁠1/2⁠ particles have a non-zero weak hypercharge.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] There are two types of weak interaction (called *vertices*).
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] The first type is called the "charged-current interaction" because the *weakly interacting* fermions form a current with total *electric* charge that is nonzero.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] The second type is called the "neutral-current interaction" because the *weakly interacting* fermions form a current with total *electric* charge of zero.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] It is responsible for the (rare) deflection of neutrinos.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] The two types of interaction follow different selection rules.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] This naming convention is often misunderstood to label the electric charge of the W and Z bosons, however the naming convention predates the concept of the mediator bosons, and clearly (at least in name) labels the charge of the current (formed from the fermions), not necessarily the bosons.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] Similarly, a down-type quark (d, s, or b, with a charge of ⁠−+ 1 /3⁠) can be converted into an up-type quark (u, c, or t, with a charge of ⁠++ 2 /3⁠), by emitting a W− boson or by absorbing a W+ boson.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] More precisely, the down-type quark becomes a quantum superposition of up-type quarks: that is to say, it has a possibility of becoming any one of the three up-type quarks, with the probabilities given in the CKM matrix tables.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] The W boson is unstable so will rapidly decay, with a very short lifetime.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] Decay of a W boson to other products can happen, with varying probabilities.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] In the so-called beta decay of a neutron (see picture, above), a down quark within the neutron emits a virtual W− boson and is thereby converted into an up quark, converting the neutron into a proton.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] Because of the limited energy involved in the process (i.e., the mass difference between the down quark and the up quark), the virtual W− boson can only carry sufficient energy to produce an electron and an electron-antineutrino – the two lowest-possible masses among its prospective decay products.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] In neutral current interactions, a quark or a lepton (e.g., an electron or a muon) emits or absorbs a neutral Z boson.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] The quantum number *weak charge* (Qw) serves the same role in the neutral current interaction with the Z0 that electric charge (Q, with no subscript) does in the electromagnetic interaction: It quantifies the vector part of the interaction.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] Since the weak mixing angle ⁠ $\theta _{\mathsf {w}}\approx 29^{\circ }$ ⁠, the parenthetic expression ⁠ $(1-4\,\sin ^{2}\theta _{\mathsf {w}})\approx 0.060$ ⁠, with its value varying slightly with the momentum difference (called "*running*") between the particles involved.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] since by convention ⁠ $\operatorname {sgn} T_{3}\equiv \operatorname {sgn} Q$ ⁠, and for all fermions involved in the weak interaction ⁠ $T_{3}=\pm {\tfrac {1}{2}}$ ⁠.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] The weak charge of charged leptons is then close to zero, so these mostly interact with the Z boson through the axial coupling.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] The Standard Model of particle physics describes the electromagnetic interaction and the weak interaction as two different aspects of a single electroweak interaction.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] This theory was developed around 1968 by Sheldon Glashow, Abdus Salam, and Steven Weinberg, and they were awarded the 1979 Nobel Prize in Physics for their work.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] The Higgs mechanism provides an explanation for the presence of three massive gauge bosons (W+ , W− , Z0 , the three carriers of the weak interaction), and the photon (γ, the massless gauge boson that carries the electromagnetic interaction).
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] According to the electroweak theory, at very high energies, the universe has four components of the Higgs field whose interactions are carried by four massless scalar bosons forming a complex scalar Higgs field doublet.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] Likewise, there are four massless electroweak vector bosons, each similar to the photon.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] However, at low energies, this gauge symmetry is spontaneously broken down to the U(1) symmetry of electromagnetism, since one of the Higgs fields acquires a vacuum expectation value.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] Naïvely, the symmetry-breaking would be expected to produce three massless bosons, but instead those "extra" three Higgs bosons become incorporated into the three weak bosons, which then acquire mass through the Higgs mechanism.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] These three composite bosons are the W+ , W− , and Z0 bosons actually observed in the weak interaction.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] The fourth electroweak gauge boson is the photon (γ) of electromagnetism, which does not couple to any of the Higgs fields and so remains massless.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] This theory has made a number of predictions, including a prediction of the masses of the Z and W bosons before their discovery and detection in 1983.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] By 14 March 2013, a Higgs boson was tentatively confirmed to exist.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] In a speculative case where the electroweak symmetry breaking scale were lowered, the unbroken SU(2) interaction would eventually become confining.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] Alternative models where SU(2) becomes confining above that scale appear quantitatively similar to the Standard Model at lower energies, but dramatically different above symmetry breaking.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] The laws of nature were long thought to remain the same under mirror reflection.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] The results of an experiment viewed via a mirror were expected to be identical to the results of a separately constructed, mirror-reflected copy of the experimental apparatus watched through the mirror.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] This so-called law of parity conservation was known to be respected by classical gravitation, electromagnetism and the strong interaction; it was assumed to be a universal law.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] However, in the mid-1950s Chen-Ning Yang and Tsung-Dao Lee suggested that the weak interaction might violate this law.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] Chien Shiung Wu and collaborators in 1957 discovered that the weak interaction violates parity, earning Yang and Lee the 1957 Nobel Prize in Physics.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] Although the weak interaction was once described by Fermi's theory, the discovery of parity violation and renormalization theory suggested that a new approach was needed.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] In 1957, Robert Marshak and George Sudarshan and, somewhat later, Richard Feynman and Murray Gell-Mann proposed a V − A (vector minus axial vector or left-handed) Lagrangian for weak interactions.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] In this theory, the weak interaction acts only on left-handed particles (and right-handed antiparticles).
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] Since the mirror reflection of a left-handed particle is right-handed, this explains the maximal violation of parity.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] The *V − A* theory was developed before the discovery of the Z boson, so it did not include the right-handed fields that enter in the neutral current interaction.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] However, this theory allowed a compound symmetry CP to be conserved.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] CP combines parity P (switching left to right) with charge conjugation C (switching particles with antiparticles).
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] Physicists were again surprised when in 1964, James Cronin and Val Fitch provided clear evidence in kaon decays that *CP* symmetry could be broken too, winning them the 1980 Nobel Prize in Physics.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] In 1973, Makoto Kobayashi and Toshihide Maskawa showed that *CP* violation in the weak interaction required more than two generations of particles, effectively predicting the existence of a then unknown third generation.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] This discovery earned them half of the 2008 Nobel Prize in Physics.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] Unlike parity violation, *CP* violation occurs only in rare circumstances.
[src:standard-model/weak-interaction] Despite its limited occurrence under present conditions, it is widely believed to be the reason that there is much more matter than antimatter in the universe, and thus forms one of Andrei Sakharov's three conditions for baryogenesis.
